<html>
<head>
<title>Buckley: The Problem of the Fatherless Child I -- 2/6/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
New York, February 6, 1996
</i>

<h2>
The Problem of the Fatherless Child I
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/
buckley
.html">
William F. Buckley Jr.
</a>

<P>
The weekend paper ran a cartoon by Mike Smith of the North American 
Syndicate. In a sequence, the freckled little girl with long hair, 
reproduced eight times with eight balloons, tells us what she is 
thinking: "This is Cindy." "Cindy is 13 years old." "Which means she 
can't drink." "She can't drive." "She can't even buy cigarettes." 
"Which is all the better for the health and safety . . . of her 
daughter." 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In October, in this space, I designated the single-parent household, 
as so many others have, as the primary social problem in America. I 
meditated that since the steep rise in illegitimate births over the 
past thirty years (from 5 per cent to 18 per cent among whites; 25 to 
63 per cent among blacks) few ideas have crystallized on how to arrest 
a development that is afflicting one million children per year (they 
will in their lifetime -- mostly before they reach maturity -- run a 
600 per cent greater chance than children raised by two parents of 
life in poverty, criminal activity, addiction to drugs, illiteracy). 
The single novel idea, developed at systematic length, is that of 
Charles Murray, who in his book Losing Ground endorsed an end to 
public welfare as a disincentive to sexual promiscuity (and to sloth). 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
I asked readers to share with me their own suggestions on how to deal 
with the problem. The reply was overwhelming, over eight hundred 
letters, and I take this opportunity to thank them deeply and to 
apologize for the mechanical impossibility of acknowledging them 
individually.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
There is no mistaking the anger out there. It tends to focus on that 
which is most palpable: The cost imposed on the individual whose 
sexual activity is conventional, by those who proceed to produce 
children who then become, in virtue of the father's absence and 
dereliction, charges to them. One mother writes that she thinks it 
wrong, somehow, that her daughter and son-in-law are postponing a 
family until their material fortunes improve, yet find themselves 
helping to pay for the support of other mothers who do not postpone 
motherhood until after they are married.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Some who complain focus on the moral dereliction of the here-today 
gone-tomorrow sire, some focus primarily on the utilitarian question: 
What to do about people who misbehave in a world in which misbehavior 
is usually not defined in a moral context. It may be legal misbehavior 
to deny an opportunity for equal treatment to a minority 18-year old, 
but it is not legal misbehavior to deny equal treatment to an infant 
born out of wedlock.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But some do focus on the quite extraordinary insouciance of the young 
generation of studs. One lawyer from South Dakota who has heard "over 
seven hundred child-support cases" sends along a transcript (the names 
of the principals are blacked out), of an illuminating example.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The situation was as follows. The young defendant is brought in to 
answer for his failure to send the required check to the mother of two 
of his children. We learn that he has sired a third child by another 
woman, and his complaint is that he simply cannot earn enough money to 
satisfy the demands being made on him, and the court simply has to 
recognize this.
<p>
REFEREE: So you're saying that you're going to hide out from the child 
support obligation?
<p>
DAD: I would if need be.<p> 
REFEREE: You know it's possible that could be a felony?
<p>
DAD: Yes, I know that.
<p>
REFEREE: You, I assume voluntarily engaged in intercourse with each of 
those women, is that much correct?
<p>
DAD: Mm-hmm.
<p>
REFEREE: And the consequence was that on at least three occasions 
these women conceived and had children?
<p>
DAD: Yeah.
<p>
REFEREE: And that certainly isn't society's fault.
<p>
DAD: I never said it was.
<p>
REFEREE: You know, society's not treating you unfairly. You weren't 
required to have any children.
<p>
DAD: Well, I don't think it's, you know, up to society to not let me 
have a living at the same time, either. . . . There's got to be a 
compromise so the State can be happy and I can be happy too.
<p> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Respondents were all but unanimous in asking the law to bear down on 
the fathers, mostly absent. Some suggest DNA tests immediately after 
birth, when more often than not the father shows up proudly, even if 
it is only for a few weeks: do a DNA on the baby and the father, to 
preserve perpetual evidence of biological responsibility. And then, 
not a few respondents ask, Why is it not criminal, the activity we 
speak of?


<P><P>

<P>
<center>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]

<br>

</blockquote></blockquote>




