</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Buckley:  New York Live</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg"><center><i>NEW YORK, OCTOBER 27</i><hr><h2>New York Live</h2><br><a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>
New York City early in the week was just the place to sharpen up on 
political and social protocol, Messrs. Giuliani and Rangel acting as 
dancing masters. The headlines went to the mayor, who sent two 
bouncers to Lincoln Center to escort Yasir Arafat out of the theater. 
This was done, apparently, even though the Palestinian delegation had 
received three tickets for the concert organized by the mayor for his 
international diplomats. The ouster was hailed by Mr. Giuliani's most 
intimate associates, condemned by everyone else, the State Department 
apoplectic in the matter. Mr. Giuliani's point was that as a 
prosecutor years ago he had handled, or been given to study, instances 
of terrorism done by Arafat and his organization. He would not, he 
declared to the press, serve as gracious host to anyone who had 
engaged in terrorism. 
<p>
That position can empty the house, of course. The former prime 
minister of Israel, Menachem Begin, not only participated in terrorist 
activity, he headed up Irgun, a terrorist organization. Nelson 
Mandela, even in jail, headed up an organization that proudly and 
defiantly exercised and defended terrorism. But if Mayor Giuliani had 
led President Mandela from the floor, he'd have provoked the black 
community, and maybe even would have violated one of the civil-rights 
laws. President Jiang Zemin of China is not too old to have 
participated in the Cultural Revolution, sustained by acts of state 
terrorism designed to tranquilize inquisitive children. And of course 
we had Castro.
<p>
Castro is a continuing phenomenon. After his opening speech at the UN 
he donned his battle fatigues and went up to Harlem, where he was 
treated as O.J. would have been if he had killed two women, not just 
one. Representative Charlie Rangel gave and got a bear hug, a 
significant emotional advancement for a man who only a few years ago 
railed against any commerce, diplomatic or material, with South 
Africa. <p>

The curious were entitled to wonder exactly why. Why should Democratic 
die-hard Charles Rangel be enthusiastic about the accomplishments of 
Fidel Castro? To begin with, there are no accomplishments save for 
full employment for prison guards and executioners. The only 
significant accomplishment of Fidel Castro is to have kept himself 
alive, given that there are at least a million Cubans who would gladly 
pull the trap on any scaffold on which Fidel Castro was poised. And 
staying alive was a considerable achievement, given that the United 
States' Operation Mongoose made several attempts to assassinate him, 
including one that dispatched for his use a scuba-diving suit that 
after a few minutes would transform itself into a host of piranhas; 
and, on another occasion, a superb cigar, except that it was designed 
to explode after two or three draws. On this matter, Fidel had himself 
a good laugh, when he told his audience in Harlem that he was not 
participating in State Department ceremonies because he didn't want to 
"interfere in this country's foreign affairs." 
<p>
Castro was received at the Council on Foreign Relations, which is okay 
given that the CFR flat-out invites any state leader, no questions 
asked, to its chambers to discuss that leader's line. And then also 
Castro dined privately with twenty establishment figures. Among them 
was Robert McNamara, defense secretary at the time Castro was 
receiving nuclear missiles aimed at the United States. We must suppose 
that Secretary McNamara apologized for acting so peremptorily back in 
1962 when he demanded the withdrawal of the missiles. We like to think 
that Castro was big about it and forgave McNamara. 
<p>
He was after all in an expansive mood, boasting that there were more 
doctors per capita in Cuba than in the United States and offering to 
send to America a few doctors to look after Americans in need. We were 
reminded of Eva Peron, who in 1949 offered straightfacedly to send 
clothes for the underclad children in Washington. . . . <p>And all the 
while New Yorkers thought that the burlesque was on Broadway.
<p><br><center>[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Other Columns </a>]<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]<br><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center>
</body></html>
</DOC>
