</DOCHDR>
<html><title>Buckley:  Have You Ever Had Terminal Blah Time? -- 12/15/95</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center>
<i>NEW YORK, DECEMBER 15</i>
<hr>
<h2>Have You Ever Had Terminal Blah Time?</h2><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>
<P>
We confront, from our pillars of light, every problem that plagues or 
threatens to plague mankind, of every variety. Columnists have written 
on how best to avoid a war or how best to become involved in a war or 
how best to make a Floating Island. With less than a few keystrokes, 
the opinion makers can redesign the Cathedral of Chartres, advising 
where all the mistakes were made, and how they might be avoided. 
Scientific contentions having to do with the best mineral for 
preserving human teeth can become causes celcbres and contestants will 
stand their ground with all their weapons oiled, well poised to 
discredit a silly argument from the other side. But what happens when 
you are sick? 
<P>
A bizarre question, because incapacitating illnesses don't . . . seem 
to happen. We are all familiar with the law that the charismatic 
leader must appear to be immune to the abrasions that hinder mere men 
and women. Sensing this, though the idea was not yet explicated, FDR 
took pains to disguise his infirmity. Fidel Castro, we learned soon 
after his ascendancy in Cuba, simply cancelled all public engagements 
when feeling ill. In such a society as he rules over, it is easier to 
do this than it would be, say, in America, where arbitrary action is 
accepted only when caused by nature. You can cancel a game in the 
World Series because a hurricane got in the way, but not because Joe 
DiMaggio didn't feel well. In 1985 in Washington the weather was so 
cold that the whole inaugural parade was put off. That meant the 
President could not take his oath of office in the usual place, so he 
took it instead in the rotunda of the House of Representatives. And 
everyone knew that it was actually a re-enactment, because the 
constitutional date for taking the office had come the day before, but 
they don't like doing these things on a Sunday.
<P>
But what if one were really sick? A gentleman sent down two weeks ago 
for execution pleaded a postponement on the grounds that he was 
suffering from a terrible head cold and could not take in his own 
execution and that surely this was one of the designs of death-
sentence architects. Suppose that the Queen of England were to be 
crowned on Tuesday and that morning she announced to the Court that 
she simply was not up to it, that sitting up there on the throne for 
two or three hours would constitute a torture she'd find unbearable. 
What then?
<P>
What if she faced the same hideous plight as the columnist stricken 
with some combination of cold, sinus, nose-clog, throat-tightening 
even after two days of antibiotics, when time comes for him to produce 
. . . a column? 
<P>
There are ways to go that dramatize your immobility. Wanda Landowska 
slightly messed up one fugue from a sonata and then closed her 
harpsichord, permanently. Toscanini reacted similarly to a lapse of 
memory. Franz Liszt decided he would no longer perform before large 
audiences and ostentatiously pulled down the piano cover after he was 
through. The statesman of high office is less prone to apocalyptic 
departures from public life, though Charles de Gaulle did that 
exactly. 
<P>
What irks the quotidian analyst is the triviality of the challenge. I 
am not John McCain, whom one would have understood if he had ended any 
attempt at communication after five years in the Vietnamese prison 
camps. It is just, in the great scheme of things, one spark plug that 
won't ignite, not even after submitting it to the one-hundredth 
homeopathic distraction. 
<P>
So that, burrow as you might in these lines in search of an apercu 
worth pocketing, forgive me; my cupboard is bare. <p>

<br><center>

[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]

