</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Chavez: Black Racism Goes Largely Unchallenged  --1/4/96
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>




<center><i>January 4, 1996</i>
<hr>
<h2>Black Racism Goes Largely Unchallenged </h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 



 
"The problem of the twentieth century is the problem of the color 
line," W.E.B. Du Bois predicted in 1900. Unfortunately, his words 
still ring true in 1996 but with a bitter irony. In 1900 blacks stood 
on one side of the color line as victims of racism. Today, increasing 
numbers of blacks have crossed over the line to become perpetrators of 
racism as well. And while we have become far more courageous in 
condemning and punishing racism when it is practiced by whites, black 
racism goes largely unchallenged. Witness the reactions to two 
murderous attacks by racists last month.
<p>
In the first incident, two white soldiers are accused of viciously 
murdering a black couple in Fayetteville, N.C., because the men hated 
blacks. The murder was front-page news across the country and led the 
evening network broadcasts. The Army, concerned the suspects might be 
part of an organized network of white supremacists, launched a full-
scale investigation to weed out any racist fringe groups.
<p>
The second incident took place just one day after the racially 
motivated murder of the black couple in North Carolina. A black man 
entered a white-owned store in Harlem, warning blacks to leave, before 
he opened fire on the mostly Hispanic and white employees and 
customers and then set the store ablaze. When the conflagration ended, 
eight people, including the gunman, were dead. The story generated 
only moderate news attention outside New York and little national 
soul-searching about the causes or prevalence of black racism. Only a 
small handful of national columnists deemed the racial aspects of the 
homicidal rampage worthy of specific condemnation, and most of these 
were black journalists.
<p>
If the Harlem murders were an isolated event, the reluctance of so 
many white opinion leaders to confront black racism might be 
understandable. But black-on-white hate crimes have increased 
dramatically. In one study by Klanwatch, a liberal civil rights group 
that monitors racist incidents, nearly half the racially motivated 
murders over three years were committed by blacks, who are only 12% of 
the population.
<p>
Media reticence to condemn black racism reflects an insidious double 
standard. White racism is rightly viewed as a moral failing of the 
individual and as a threat to both the peace and justice of society. 
But many in the media seem reluctant to gauge black racism in the same 
way.
<p>
For weeks before the attack on the white-owned Harlem store, 
demonstrators marched in front of the building, shouting racist and 
anti-Semitic remarks. According to the testimony of the Jewish store 
owner, who sought a restraining order against the demonstrators prior 
to the murders, protesters "made motions of striking a match and 
throwing it on the outside clothing displays or into the doorway of 
the store." Days before the actual arson, he warned prophetically: "At 
some point real matches will be thrown at me and my store. This is not 
an idle fear on my part."<p>     But in the heart of the media capital of 
the world - New York City - this story of vicious hate-mongering went 
unreported until after the fire. Is it imaginable that a similar story 
of white protesters making such threatening gestures outside a black-
owned establishment would be ignored by the media?
<p>
In some circles, blacks are presumed incapable of racism because they 
lack power. But racism is about hate, not power. It takes hate, not 
power, to shoot an innocent couple on a deserted street or set fire to 
a store full of frightened people.
<p>
And it takes considerable cowardice not to recognize hate comes in all 
colors. 
<P>
<center><hr width="50%">



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
