<html><head><title>Chavez: Hillary Furor: Greed, Not Deception, At Issue  --1/19/96
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>




<center><i>January 19, 1996</i>
<hr>
<h2>Hillary Furor: Greed, Not Deception, At Issue</h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> Linda  Chavez



 
 
The entire Washington press corps and scores of politicians 
seem obsessed the last few weeks with finding out whether Hillary 
Clinton is telling the truth. But deception isn't the heart of 
the scandals and controversies swirling around the first lady - 
greed is. The Clintons' greed, as well as that of their friends, 
is the root of the problems afflicting the first couple, from 
Whitewater, to Hillary's dubious commodity trades, to the firing 
of White House travel office personnel. This an old-fashioned 
story about graft and corruption - the kind that has been the 
undoing of many a politician. 
 <P>
The trouble began in 1978, when Bill Clinton was the poorly 
paid, young attorney general of Arkansas and Hillary was not yet 
the $ 125-an-hour partner in the successful Rose Law Firm. James 
McDougal, an Arkansas businessman with more chutzpah than 
scruples, approached the couple with an offer they couldn't 
refuse: Become business partners in a potentially lucrative land 
deal, and he'd make them rich. 
 <P>
The Clintons had no real money to invest - they didn't even 
own a home - but that didn't matter. McDougal was willing to give 
them a 50% share of 230 acres on the White River, to be purchased 
entirely with borrowed money from a bank willing to accept the 
partners' signatures as collateral for a $ 203,000 loan. (Try 
that with your local bank the next time you see property you'd 
like to own but can't afford.) 
 <P>
Although both Bill and Hillary graduated with honors from Yale 
Law School, they seem not to have questioned the legality, much 
less propriety, of accepting something for nothing. Nor did the 
Clintons trouble themselves about ethics as the land deal went 
sour, requiring more shady borrowing, and their business partner 
McDougal became enmeshed in the savings and loan scandal that 
cost taxpayers billions. 
 <P>
Although Whitewater itself never produced the profits McDougal 
promised, it gave the Clintons some hefty tax write-offs as their 
incomes increased with Hillary's growing law practice. And 
McDougal even threw Hillary some legal business as well, a 
$2,000-per-month retainer he says the then-governor personally 
solicited (though Bill Clinton denies it). 
 <P>
And while Whitewater didn't become a cash cow, Hillary made a 
bundle in another bovine adventure: the cattle futures commodity 
market. The Clintons reaped a $ 100,000 profit on a $ 1,000 
investment, again with help from an Arkansas businessman, James 
Blair. As general counsel of Tyson's Foods, one of Arkansas' 
biggest employers and an industry regulated by the state, Blair 
did plenty of business with the state while he was fattening the 
Clintons' bank account. Neither the governor nor his 
attorney-wife questioned the lawfulness of letting Blair place 
trades on Hillary's behalf or pocketing the proceeds. 
 <P>
Even Travelgate boils down to greed - on the part of Clinton 
chums, if not the president and his wife. Although most of the 
attention has focused on whether Hillary Clinton ordered the 
firing of the White House travel office staff, there's much more 
to the story. An article by Byron York in the Jan. 22 issue of 
The Weekly Standard documents the attempt by a Clinton friend and 
his business associate to take over all of the federal 
government's non-military aircraft business, not just the 
chartered press travel run out of the White House. Had the flap 
not developed when the White House firings took place, this plan 
would have gone forward, netting millions of dollars in profits 
to Clinton's friends. 
 <P>
The Clintons may have railed against the Republicans' "decade 
of greed," but all the while they were trying to line their own - 
and their friends' - pockets. 

<P>
<center><hr width="50%">



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
