<html>
<head>
<title>Chavez: Author Fires Potshots While Hiding Identity  -- 2/8/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
February 8, 1996
</i>

<h2>Author Fires Potshots While Hiding Identity
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">
Linda  Chavez </a>
<P>
 
Ever wonder why so many Americans are turned off by politics, 
politicians, journalists and nearly everything having to do with 
Washington? (Except maybe its monuments and museums?)

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Maybe all the fuss generated by "Primary Colors" -- the new, 
anonymously written novel about the 1992 Clinton campaign -- provides 
a clue.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It's the ultimate insider's tale about a world that few on the outside 
know or care about, and it's preoccupying a good deal of the nation's 
capital. The novel itself and the controversy it has generated are 
testaments to all that is petty, insular and creepy about political 
Washington.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using the techniques of a roman a clef (which means literally "novel 
with a key"), the story reads like a political edition of the game 
Trivial Pursuit.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The story involves a young, ambitious governor of a small Southern 
state whose presidential campaign is plagued by scandals.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If you don't know who Mandy Grunwald, Betsy Wright and Stanley 
Greenberg are (they're actual Clinton operatives), you'll probably get 
lost trying to decipher the book's elaborate cast of characters. Which 
seems to be the author's aim: Create cardboard-cutout characters 
immediately recognizable to Washington sophisticates but of little 
interest to the rest of the world, then hope the pundits create a 
large enough buzz to sell lots of books.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The plan seems to be working. "Primary Colors" hits No. 1 this week on 
USA TODAY's best-seller list.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of this might be harmless enough were it not for two insidious 
aspects of the book.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was written either by someone inside the Clinton operation or a 
reporter with access to intimate details of the campaign, and it 
contains every vicious, undubstantiated rumor ever circulated about 
Bill or Hillary Clinton.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Washington officials, pundits and the press corps are too busy trying 
to guess who wrote the novel to waste much indignation on the ethics, 
much less propriety, of the venture. But surely there is something 
wrong when either a former campaign worker or a journalist can make 
money anonymously peddling smarmy gossip about the president of the 
United States and his wife.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Staff loyalty is a virtue that has long since disappeared in 
Washington. Presidential aides no longer wait until their boss is out 
of office (much less dead) to write intimate tell-alls -- and 
Republican presidents fare no better than Democrates. But "Primary 
Colors" breaks new ground in the kiss-and-tell genre. By remaining 
anonymous, the author keeps his or her reputation intact -- at least 
temporarily -- while ravaging others'.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most disturbing possibility is that the book was written not by 
someone inside the campaign but by a journalist. The novel reeks of a 
strange, hybrid bias -- it exudes both admiration and contempt for the 
Clintons.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whoever wrote the book is a fan of the Clintons' politics but clearly 
not of their moral character. Journalists are entitled to their biases 
and opinions -- so long as they're stated up front. That's why 
newspapers have editorial and opinion pages. But journalists are not 
free to weave their prejudices into their reporting.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor should they be free to slander public figures through thinly 
veiled fiction while keeping their own identities secret.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;I'm no fan of the Clintons, but they deserve better than this.


<P><P>


</blockquote></blockquote>

<center>
<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.


<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
