<html><head><title>Chavez: As In Israel, We Need to Tone Down Rhetoric
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><i>November 10, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>As In Israel, We Need to Tone Down Rhetoric</h2> 
<P><a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 


The murder of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin by an extreme 
Israeli nationalist should be a warning to all political groups that 
words have consequences. Since the signing of the first peace accord 
with the Palestinians in 1993, some opponents of the agreement have 
attacked Rabin in the most vicious and personal terms. Rabin was 
depicted as a traitor to his country, a murderer, even a Nazi SS 
officer.
<p>
Vilifying political opponents isn't unique to Israeli politics, nor 
are the dangers that go with such angry rhetoric. In recent months 
Democrats in Congress have called Republicans "worse than Hitler" and 
accused them of "practicing genocide with a smile." Meanwhile, 
Republicans have called Democrats "the enemy  of normal Americans," 
and the right-leaning National Rifle Association has portrayed federal 
law enforcement agents as jack-booted storm troopers.
<p>
The First Amendment gives us the right to call each other Nazis or 
enemies, but constitutional protection doesn't make it right. 
Responsible leaders have an obligation to refrain from engaging in 
such tactics and to discourage the behavior among their supporters. 
That doesn't mean we have to stifle political debate. The danger on 
any issue comes when the focus of criticism shifts from disparaging 
the policy to demonizing the policymakers. That dangerous game can 
have deadly consequences.
<p>
There seems to be a growing tendency to portray our political 
opponents not only as wrong but evil. When Democrats attack 
Republicans, they portray them as  callous and greedy, wanting to take 
food from the mouths of poor children to give money to the rich. 
Republicans engage in similar demonization, calling Democrats un-
American and immoral.
<p>
Politicians poison public debate when they turn policy differences 
into attacks on their opponents' character, ethics, patriotism and 
morality. What's more, they make legitimate compromise more difficult 
-- and public cynicism inevitable.
<p>
What will happen when the Democrats and Republicans agree on a budget 
-- as they must eventually? What will happen when the Congress reverts 
to Democratic control -- or a Republican occupies the White House? 
Will any of these events portend national disaster? Do they justify a 
revolution?
<p>
One of the saving graces of American politics has been its centrist 
nature. The ideological difference between Republicans and Democrats 
has never been as great as between the Conservative and Labor parties 
in England, not to mention as wide as the chasm that separates neo-
fascist and pro-communist groups in other European democracies.
<p>
Following Rabin's assassination, Benjamin Netanyahu, the leader of the 
opposition Likud Party in Israel and a critic of Rabin's peace plan, 
said the most important thing Israelis could do was to pull together 
as a nation and a people.
<p>
Americans face no crisis comparable to the Israelis' at the moment, 
but Netanyahu's advice could serve us well nonetheless. We've had our 
share of extremist individuals - on both the right and the left - who 
have engaged not only in assassinations but domestic terrorism.
<p>
Politicians in Israel, especially on the right, will be soul-searching 
to determine whether their words might have incited extremists in 
their midst to violence. We could do with some similar examination of 
conscience here at home. 
<hr width="50%">
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a><p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</body>

</html>  


