HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 10-Feb-97 15:12:40 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 03-Jun-96 21:02:02 GMT
Content-length: 4477
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Chavez: Immigrants Make Gains in California
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><i>November 16, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>Immigrants Make Gains in California</h2> 
<P><a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 
 
 
Californians still have earthquakes, mudslides and fires to worry 
about, but they can breathe a little easier when it comes to another 
perennial source of anxiety: the state's 6 million immigrants.
<p>
A new study by the University of Southern California shows that the 
region's immigrants are rapidly moving into the social and economic 
mainstream despite fears they would be a huge burden.
<p>
The study, by USC's School of Urban and Regional Planning, details 
impressive gains in income, status and English proficiency among the 
largest immigrant groups, including Asians and Latinos who arrived in 
the 1970s.
<p>
Using census data from 1980 and 1990, the USC researchers found that 
Asian immigrants in Southern California who were between 25 to 34 
years old in 1980 had more than doubled their average income by 1990.
<p>
Nearly 70 percent became U.S. citizens in the same period. And more 
than half spoke English very well.
<p>
Immigrants of the same age from Europe and the Middle East made 
similar gains in income and even more spectacular gains in English 
proficiency, though only 51 percent became citizens.
<p>
Even Latino immigrants had made significant progress, improving their 
earnings by 27 percent.
<p>
Although relatively few Latinos who came to the U.S. as adults spoke 
English  very well (only 21 percent of those who were 25 to 34 in 
1980), 70 percent of those who immigrated as children were fully 
proficient in English by 1990.
<p>
But if California immigrants are doing so well, why have their fellow 
state residents turned sour on immigration?
<p>
 Nearly half of registered voters in the state - including 28 percent 
of Hispanic voters - believe there is no benefit whatsoever from 
immigration, according to a recent Los Angeles Times poll.
<p>
And Californians aren't alone in their hostility to immigrants. Nearly 
two out of three Americans say immigrants are "a bad thing for this 
country" and will never assimilate.
<p>
The problem may have to do with more than simple prejudice.
<p>
With so many new immigrants coming to the United States now - about 
800,000 were admitted last year - it's difficult to measure their 
progress.
<p>
Simply comparing how all immigrants measure up on education, language, 
earnings and the like from 1980 to 1990 tells almost nothing about 
those immigrants who actually lived in the U.S. for that entire 10-
year period.
<p>
Why? Because the group measured in 1990 isn't composed of the same 
people as  the one measured in 1980.
<p>
The newer immigrants - by definition - haven't lived in the U.S. as 
long and  won't have had as much time to improve their status.
<p>
The USC researchers got around this problem by analyzing census data 
differently.
<p>
Instead of looking at all immigrants in 1980 and 1990, they broke up 
immigrants into groups based on their ethnic background, age and time 
of arrival.
<p>
The USC researchers then tracked these "cohorts" in the census of both 
1980 and 1990.
<p>
This allowed researchers to compare the same group 10 years apart.
<p>
The more accurate analysis can demonstrate what improvements similar 
groups of immigrants make in learning English, becoming citizens and 
increasing their incomes.
<p>
Too bad the USC study won't be widely read by those in or out of 
California.  It could be an important antidote to the anti-immigrant 
sentiment sweeping the country.
<p>
The USC data dispel many of the myths about immigrants: that they're 
stuck on the bottom rung of the economic ladder, that they can't or 
won't assimilate and that they'll never become Americans.
<p>
At the very least, the study should be required reading for members of 
Congress, who will soon vote on major legislation that could 
dramatically reduce immigration.


 
<center><hr width="50%">
<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br><p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</body>

</html>  
