</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Chavez: Murders Show Evil Can Exist Anywhere
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><i>November 30, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>Murders Show Evil Can Exist Anywhere</h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 
 
  
Just last week in Illinois, Jacqueline Williams was accused of ripping 
an unborn baby from his murdered mother's womb.
<p>
Barely had the gruesome details faded from the headlines when two more 
ghastly stories appeared in which women were suspects in the horrific 
murders of their own children.
<p>
In Olathe, Kan., a 44-year-old doctor, Debora Green, was charged with 
setting fire to her own home and killing two of her three children. 
Green also is suspected of attempting to poison her estranged husband 
earlier this year, although charges have yet to be filed.
<p>
In New York, a 29-year-old woman, Awilda Lopez, was arrested for 
killing her  6-year-old daughter by hitting her in the head with a 
blunt object. Police who investigated the crime said the child bore 
numerous scars from cigarette burns and bruises over her whole body.
<p>
Who are these monster-women?
<p>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich blamed the Illinois murders, which 
included not only the dead mother but also two of her other children, 
on the welfare state.
<p>
Welfare policy has created "a drug-addicted underclass with no sense 
of humanity, no sense of civilization and no sense of the rules of 
life," Gingrich  told a Republican governors meeting shortly after the 
bizarre murders and kidnapping were reported.
<p>
If only it were as simple as that.
<p>
Yes, welfare policy has led to growing social pathology in this 
society. Welfare rewards people for not working, frees men from the 
financial responsibility for their children and encourages women to 
remain unwed if they become pregnant.
<p>
And certainly both the Illinois and New York murders took place in an 
underclass environment.
<p>
Although not all the details are yet known in the Williams case, drugs 
probably played some role. And Awilda Lopez, who was indicted Tuesday, 
was clearly involved in drugs: Her daughter was born addicted to crack 
cocaine.
<p>
Women who commit crimes are even more likely than men to be regular 
drug users: 65% of female prison inmates compared with 62% of males 
are regular drug  users, and 36% of women vs. 31% of men were using 
drugs when they committed the  crimes for which they are incarcerated.
<p>
But the problems go far deeper than drugs, welfare and the underclass.
<p>
Dr. Green is a wealthy, well-educated woman living in small-town 
America. Susan Smith, who was convicted earlier this year of drowning 
her two sons after  claiming they'd been kidnapped, also came from a 
respected, middle-class family.
<p>
What is so horrifyingly inexplicable about the murders of the Green 
and Smith children is that they don't seem to have been committed by 
women driven crazy by drugs or poverty.
<p>
These were coldblooded, calculated murders by women who seemed to lead 
ordinary, even privileged, lives. It's the very familiarity of these 
women's experiences that makes so chilling the evil they perpetrated.
<p>
Stories of women who murder their own children have shocked and 
fascinated us for thousands of years. No figure in Greek mythology 
invokes more dread or loathing than Medea, who killed her own children 
to punish their father, Jason,  for his infidelity.
<p>
In Euripedes' play of the same name, Medea is described by Jason as a 
"hateful thing, you woman most utterly loathed by the gods and me and 
all the race of mankind."
<p>
Last year 538 children in the United States were killed by their 
parents (compared with 308 parents killed by their own children).
<p>
The Justice Department doesn't publish statistics showing how many 
mothers vs. fathers killed their children, although it is difficult to 
imagine that murders by mothers constituted more than a small fraction 
of the total. Difficult to imagine because there is no more horrible 
or unnatural crime than a mother taking the life of her own child.
<p>
Sometimes no amount of analysis or explanation or blame shifting will 
allow us to avoid looking evil straight in the face - even when it 
belongs to a mother.
<p>
What is truly frightening about these recent murders is that they 
demonstrate that evil can exist anywhere, including where it seems 
most unlikely. And it is  more difficult to root out evil than to 
change public policy.
<p>
<p>

 
<center><hr width="50%">
<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br><p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</body>

</html>  


