<html><head><title>Chavez: Don't Underestimate Taxpayers' Intelligence 
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>




<center><i>December 7, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>Don't Underestimate Taxpayers' Intelligence </h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 

 
As budget negotiations near the crisis stage again next week, expect 
Democrats to demagogue on taxes as they have for the past three years. 
Although President Clinton was elected with a promise to enact a 
middle-class tax cut, he instead raised taxes in 1993. And now he and 
Democrats in Congress want Republicans to scale back the $ 245 billion 
tax cut included in their congressional budget package.
<P>
Democrats believe the key to a balanced budget is higher tax revenues, 
which they think government can magically control by manipulating tax 
rates. The theory is simple enough: Tax the rich at higher rates and 
the government will take in more revenues, which can then be used to 
pay for all those expensive government programs Democrats favor. The 
problem is, it never seems to work out  quite as intended.
<P>
A new study by Harvard Professors Martin Feldstein and Daniel Feenberg 
demonstrates why.
<P>
In 1993, the Clinton tax increase raised marginal tax rates from 31% 
to 36% on incomes between $ 140,000 and $ 250,000 and to 39.6% on 
incomes above $ 250,000. Those tax increases should have produced $ 
19.3 billion in extra revenues if the affected taxpayers had not 
changed their earnings behavior. Instead, the hefty tax hikes produced 
less than half the expected extra revenues - $ 8.4 billion.
<P>
Democrats assume taxpayers are a docile lot. Raise their taxes and 
they'll willingly fork over the extra money to the IRS. In fact, 
taxpayers - rich and not so rich - usually resist government efforts 
to take more of their money by changing their behavior. The rich, in 
particular, have lots of options to avoid  paying more to the IRS, 
including cutting back on their work effort. President Reagan was fond 
of describing his response to the confiscatory marginal tax rate of 
90% that prevailed when he was an actor. He simply quit working when 
he earned enough to put him in the highest bracket. It wasn't worth 
making that next dollar if he only got to keep 10 cents.
<P>
The study shows many wealthy Americans responded to the Clinton tax 
increases the same way. They may have worked less, taken more time 
off, bought more expensive homes with higher mortgages (shielding more 
income with higher home mortgage interest deductions), or given more 
to charity (producing higher charitable tax deductions). By whatever 
means, those in the highest brackets reduced their taxable incomes by 
an estimated 7.8%.
<P>
Some wealthy taxpayers - including Hillary Rodham Clinton - also 
avoided paying the higher 1993 taxes by shifting some of their 
expected 1993 income to 1992. Ordinary workers don't have that luxury, 
but executives, lawyers and other high-income earners sometimes do. 
They can exercise stock options or take some of their future income in 
current year bonuses if they anticipate tax increases  in future 
years. Mrs. Clinton sheltered some of her earnings by taking a year-
end bonus in 1992, thus avoiding paying the higher 1993 taxes.
<P>
It seems never to occur to Democratic politicians that many wealthy 
people got that way by being smart about money. Allow them to keep 
more of what they earn and they'll earn more, in the process creating 
jobs through their investment. But tax them excessively and they will 
figure out ways to keep Uncle Sam from getting a larger share of their 
money. Even Mrs. Clinton found a  way around the 1993 tax increase, 
temporarily putting aside Democratic ideology  when it affected her 
own pocketbook. Maybe it's time Democrats stopped underestimating the 
intelligence of U.S. taxpayers.
<center><hr width="50%">



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>

</center>
</body>

