Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Chavez: GOP Congress: '95 Something to Crow About --12/28/95 
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>




<center><i>December 28, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>GOP Congress: '95 Something to Crow About</h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 

Is the Republican revolution about to fizzle barely one year 
after it began? 
<P>
The Congress has produced no significant legislation. Extremists 
dominate the freshman class in the House. Republicans want to put poor 
children out on the streets and deprive elderly sick people of medical 
care in order to give tax breaks to the rich. The magnificent 
machinery of government has ground to a halt, not once but twice in as 
many months, causing chaos for millions of Americans. And the public 
has had enough. At least that's what the Clinton administration wants 
you to think - and the media has obligingly conveyed the message.
<P>
But before the Clintons order their favorite Arkansas champagne for 
the 1997 inaugural and House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt picks out 
new drapes for the Speaker's office, perhaps it's time to take a 
closer look at just what did happen in 1995.
<P>
The Congress of the United States actually produced a 3,000-page, 
detailed bill that will balance the budget in seven years.
<P>
Sure, the president vetoed it, but the feat is historic nonetheless. 
The Democrats couldn't come close to offering a balanced budget in 
their years at the helm - even when they controlled both the 
legislative and executive branches, as they did in the Clinton 
administration's first two years.
<P>
Republicans have taken on the first major entitlement programs - 
Medicare and Medicaid - putting principle before politics. For years, 
Republicans have been going after the small potatoes entitlements, 
such as AFDC and food stamps. These programs, while unpopular, make up 
only a small fraction of the federal budget, roughly 3%.
<P>
The really big money entitlements are Social Security and Medicare, 
which go mostly to the middle class, and Medicaid, which goes to the 
poor. These items account for more than one third of the entire 
federal budget.
<P>
Democrats have never been willing to even try to rein in these 
entitlements. But this year Republicans have risked their own re-
election in order to stop burying future generations in debt. For this 
Republicans - and especially the 73 House freshmen - have been labeled 
"extremists," not only by the president but by much of the media.
<P>
Republicans have permanently altered the terms of the debate on 
welfare. Even Democrats sound hardline about ending welfare dependency 
these days. No one argues for welfare rights' or defends welfare 
recipients who stay on the rolls year after year. And virtually 
everyone now agrees that the War on Poverty failed, not for lack of 
funds after more than $ 5 trillion spent in three decades, but because 
the programs themselves were misguided.
<P>
Democrats still cling to the demonstrably erroneous notion that 
expensive government training programs are necessary to get recipients 
off welfare and into jobs.      But when the president finally signs 
welfare reform legislation - as he must soon or face the consequences 
at the polls next year - it will bear a decidedly Republican stamp, 
devolving responsibility back to the states and giving states more 
leeway to limit dependency and discourage illegitimacy.
<P>
Republicans forced Congress to live by the same rules it cavalierly 
mandated for others and to stop accepting gifts and entertainment from 
lobbyists.
<P>
For years when Democrats controlled both Houses, Congress exempted 
itself from laws it insisted other employers obey: civil rights laws, 
health and safety laws, labor relations laws. In recent years, 
Republicans began drawing attention to this Democrat hypocrisy by 
offering amendments to make Congress subject to the same laws it 
applied to others - to no avail.
<P>
Republicans won their battle only when they won control of Congress. 
Suddenly even Democrats decided maybe no one should be above the law - 
not even Congress, now that they no longer controlled it.
<P>
The same thing happened with lobby reform. Democrats had no interest 
in lobby reform when they occupied the powerful committee 
chairmanships. But once they became backbenchers they were more than 
happy to jump on the Republican freshmen's lobby reform bandwagon.      
These Republicans accomplishments may not yet constitute a revolution. 
But they add up to the most significant legislative reforms in a 
decade - not bad for one year's effort.  
<P>
<center><hr width="50%">



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>

</center>
</body>


