<head>
<title>V-E Day Reflections</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i>Thursday, May 11, 1995 </i>
<hr>

  

<h2>V-E Day Reflections
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>










 <P>
 





Omaha Beach Cemetery, V-E Day - Beneath a clear blue sky and endless 
rows of white marble crosses lie ten thousand of the boys who set out 
to win the war. 
 <P>
They fought their way onto the continent on D-Day, and then across it 
to the Rhine and victory.  They secured the beaches and the peace for 
us, giving up their chance to live life into their old age.  On V-E 
Day, 1945, a million cheering Brits gave thanks for their bravery, 
joining  hands to sing God Save the Queen to Winston Churchill and 
Queen Elizabeth, who stood on the balcony of Buckingham Palace. 
 <P>
For millions of people, though, V-E Day was not the end of anything.  
For Poles and Czechs and Eastern Europeans, it was neither the end, 
nor even the beginning of the end, of tyranny.  It was only the 
beginning of Stalin's occupation now that Hitler's was finished.  And 
this more brutal oppression would last 44 years instead of six. 
 <P>
Oscar Lindner, an Estonian refugee, survived both.  "The only 
difference between the Germans and the Russians," he explains, "was 
that Nazis come for people during the day; Communists deport people in 
the middle of the night." 
 <P>
How ironic it is that President Clinton was neither in England nor 
France on V-E Day, but in Moscow.  The Russians, of course, have much 
to celebrate 50 years after the end of their Great Patriotic War, from 
survival of the 900 day siege of Leningrad, to the hand-to-hand battle 
in the factories and sewers of Stalingrad, which won the war and saved 
the Motherland.  But they have just as much to atone for:  the 
massacre at Katyn of the Polish officer corps, the enslavement of half 
of Europe and the crushing of freedom in Hungary in 1956 and 
Czechoslovakia in 1968. 
 <P>
So V-E Day was not the end of the anguish.  The horror of Auschwitz 
was yet to be comprehended and some 40 years of communist oppression 
lay ahead. 
 <P>
But the end of European combat began to lift an enormous weight from 
minds and hearts of Americans.  Even for those too young to fight (I 
was 10 on V-E Day), the relief was real, for the war had been with us 
for most of our young lives.   
 <P>
War bulletins, ration coupons and black-out curtains had punctuated 
our days.  Around our supper table we learned about Pearl Harbor, U-
boats, D-Day and the Seigfreid Line.  My uncle, a private in 
Eisenhower's army, was somewhere in Europe.  But where?  Near a place 
called Bastogne, it turned out, where he grabbed a butcher's cleaver 
(which he fortunately never had to use) as he turned out to meet the 
Germans pouring through the Bulge. 
 <P>
Our understanding was sharpened by the media as well, by the movies, 
newsreels, and radio.  Ingrid Bergman in the swirling mists of 
Casablanca taught us devotion to a cause; so did John Wayne in fighter 
planes and foxholes.  The endless parade of Nazi officers assuring us 
they had ways of making us talk impressed our young minds with the 
terror of the police state, while Pathe News showed us Kamikaze 
fanaticism.  Over the BBC, Winston Churchill and the Battle of Britain 
inspired us:  "never have so many owed so much to so few...this was 
their finest hour!"  Vera Lynn's haunting "I'll be seeing you..." 
reminded us that sometimes the ending would not be happy, and The Best 
Years of Our Lives brought home all the tragedies of war.  
 <P>
World War II had taught us two lasting lessons:  through effort, good 
could triumph over evil, and that our entire nation could unite to 
meet a challenge.  We shared a common determination -- "the war 
effort" --  and a clear understanding of what evil was. 
 <P>
The final lesson is how quickly that clarity faded.  The further the 
war slips from memory, the more blurred our distinction between good 
and evil has become.  In 1945, no one was for the Nazis.  By 1950,  
lots of people questioned whether South Korea even mattered.  And by 
the time of Vietnam, Jane Fonda, our universities, and our media were 
on the other side.  The tyranny of the left became acceptable only 
twenty years after we had fought a great war to destroy tyrannies of 
the right. 
 <P>
The boys buried above the cliffs of Omaha Beach would never have 
understood that.  Their cause was to free the world from the evil of 
oppression.  Its clarity is engraved in the stone of their Memorial 
Chapel:   "Remember the glory of their spirit." 
 <P>
Remember, too, that in their glory they each gave up the chance to be 
what we are today. 
 
<P> 

<P> 

<i>The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research 
institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on 
public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, 
with an office in Washington, D.C.</i>
<P>

[<a href="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi">Columnists</a>]
</html>
