<html>
<head>
<title>SCHOOL REFORM: WILL NEW JERSEY EVER LEARN?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i>Thursday, August 17, 1995 </i>
<hr>



<h2>School Reform: Will New Jersey Ever Learn?
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>










<p>
<p>
For the third time in half a dozen years, the state of New Jersey has 
seized control of a local school district.  This time the victims are 
the 48,000 students of the Newark school system, who are about to 
receive a civics lesson they will likely never forget.  They are going 
to learn what it's like to be dumped out of the frying pan of one 
failed education bureaucracy, only to fall into the fire of another. 
<p> 
There is no question that the Newark school system deserves a failing 
grade.  Only one-fourth of its students were able to pass the 1993 
high school proficiency test on their first try.  The district's 
classrooms had fallen into disrepair.  Student attendance was poor.  A 
1994 report, prepared by the state, blasted Newark school officials 
for "dereliction of duty."  The highly critical report spoke of 
students in rat-infested schools, while administrators sat in 
"comfortable offices" and had "important-sounding titles."   
<p> 
Change was obviously needed, but why do New Jersey officials believe 
that shifting control to a larger, more distant state bureaucracy is 
the right kind of change?  They have it exactly the wrong way around:  
effective school reform involves moving decisions about educating 
students closer to the classroom, not further away.  Replacing one 
bureaucracy with another will not work. 
<p> 
New Jersey officials do not have to look very far to see that this is 
so.  In the last six years, New Jersey state education officials have 
also taken control of the schools in Jersey City and Paterson.  When 
Bret Schundler became Jersey City's Mayor in 1992, its schools had 
been under state control for three years, and they continue under 
state control today.  Mayor Schundler states he is "convinced the 
takeovers are doomed to failure and can actually make matters worse."  
He notes "there has been no innovation in Paterson, no innovation in 
Jersey City, and there will probably be none in Newark." 
 <p>
A study of the Jersey City schools, conducted last year, concluded 
that the "district remains below standard in four out of five high 
schools in writing and mathematics."  Results in the district's 
elementary schools for reading and mathematics were also 
"unacceptable."  In certain areas, performance actually deteriorated 
under state control. 
 <p>
So, if state control does not work, what does?  The answer is to give 
control to teachers and parents, so teachers can teach and parents can 
choose the teachers they want for their children. 
<p> 
Suppose that six years ago, instead of commandeering their school 
system, New Jersey had allowed the parents of Jersey City to send 
their children to the school of their choice - public or private, near 
or far?  Parents could have chosen the school best suited to each of 
their children.  Newly formed charter schools might have sprung up; 
private schools might have expanded their enrollment.  Existing public 
schools would have improved to attract more students. 
 <p>
Most important, the children of Jersey City would have immediately 
begun receiving a better education.  As it worked out, Jersey City's 
30,000 students are not receiving an education today any better than 
the one the state replaced six years ago. 
 <p>
Choice and charter schools are no longer new ideas.  They are being 
tried and evaluated across the country.  In New York, East Harlem 
District No. 4 is legendary for the significant student improvement 
that occurred when teachers and parents were empowered to design and 
choose the education approach they wanted. 
 <p>
In Milwaukee, Wisconsin, an increasing number of low-income children 
are in the fifth year of a school choice program, and test scores are 
rising, although so far only slightly.  More importantly, student 
satisfaction has improved, as has parental satisfaction and 
involvement, and not surprisingly, student attendance and discipline.  
These all contribute to a learning-friendly environment that is bound 
to increase test scores even more in the future. 
 <p>
The truth is that education bureaucracies, whether the Newark school 
board, the New Jersey Department of Education, or the U. S. Department 
of Education, are simply not customer-focused.  They act like the 
monopolies they are, focusing on what is best for them. 
 <p>
The failure of these bureaucracies should be obvious to all.  SAT 
scores have fallen precipitously over the last two decades, and the 
number of students scoring 600 and above on the Verbal SATs has 
dropped 35%.  American students rank 13th in the world on math and 
science tests.  Only 26% of the fourth graders in America can actually 
read at the fourth grade level. 
 <p>
What the education bureaucrats in New Jersey and thousands of 
education departments across the country have yet to learn is that 
time and technology have passed them by.  They are industrial-age 
dinosaurs in an information-driven society, attempting to deliver 
mass-produced education to children who need individualized attention. 
 <p>
Their educational model must be replaced with the energy and 
initiative of schools free to innovate and parents empowered to do 
what is best for each of their children. 
 <p>
The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research 
institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on 
public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, 
with an office in Washington, D.C. 
<p><p>
<center>
<br>

<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">

<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body>
</html>
