<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:   MSAs Could Save Medicare -- 1/11/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 11, 1996<br></i><hr><h2> MSAs Could Save Medicare</h2></center><P> 
[Employees at the Golden Rule Insurance Company in Indianapolis are 
staunch supporters of the proposed Medicare reform called the Medical 
Savings Account. That's because all 1200 employees already have MSAs] 
 
 <P>
The Golden Rule Insurance Company is America's leading writer of 
individual health policies, with 800,000 policyholders and nearly $800 
million in annual revenue. Golden Rule is also the nation's number-one 
promoter of Medical Savings Accounts (known as MSAs), having signed 
up nearly 1000 companies for its MSA group plan. The company is so 
keen on Medical Savings Accounts that it even established an MSA 
group plan for its own employees two years ago, says reporter Bob Jones 
in a recent issue of World magazine. "Golden Rule Chairman Pat Rooney 
has made it his mission to show that MSAs actually work." 
 <P>
Jones explains the logic behind MSAs: "Health care costs will be 
controlled only when people start spending their own money instead of 
the insurance company's. To accomplish this, Medicare would offer 
seniors a new, high-deductible policy. The higher deductible means lower 
premiums; the savings are deposited to an account from which 
individuals can pay- for medical bills that fall below the deductible. 
When expenses in any year exceed the deductible," Jones continues, "the 
catastrophic insurance kicks in, paying 100 percent of remaining bills 
(instead of the 80 percent now covered by Medicare)." 
 <P>
If an individual spends less than his deductible, whatever remains in his 
MSA is "rolled over into a tax-free annuity that can be used to pay future 
medical bills or provide long-term care. This system," Jones says, 
"provides an incentive for seniors to become smart health care 
consumers, costs them no more than the current system, and at the same 
time offers more flexibility and greater benefits." 
 <P>
Under proposed Medicare reforms, "MSAs would be tax deductible like 
IRAs, making them enormously attractive not only to private businesses, 
but also to the millions of self-employed. Even without that tax 
exemption," says Jones, "MSAs have been hugely successful at a few 
pioneering companies like Golden Rule [where] health care costs 
dropped 40 percent the first year that MSAs were implemented." Medical 
Savings Accounts are even more popular among employees, says Jones, 
citing a 1994 study that found a satisfaction level of 98 percent. MSAs 
have even encouraged Golden Rule employees to take better care of 
themselves. "More than a quarter of employees are taking advantage of 
some medical service they never used before, simply because the money 
is there and they can choose how to spend it without having to worry that 
it won't be covered under their policy," says Jones. 
 <P>
The current Medicare trust fund surplus of $130 billion is expected to 
dwindle to zero in seven years. "By 2004," says Jones, "Medicare will 
face a deficit of more than $100 billion." Medical Savings Accounts are 
just what the doctor ordered to avert that grim prospect. 
 
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
