<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Judicial Usurpation -- 1/12/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 12, 1996
<br></i><hr><h2>Judicial Usurpation</h2></center><P> 
 
[By extending rights to illegal aliens, federal judges undermine the value 
of American citizenship and de-legitimize self-government.]
<P>
Washington Times columnist Paul Craig Roberts warns that self-
government may be "a thing of the past" in America. He cites a federal 
judge's recent order blocking implementation of California's Proposition 
187, which received 59 percent of the votes cast in a statewide election in 
1994. "The judge," says Roberts, "ruled that the right of illegal aliens to 
publicly-provided benefits, such as education and welfare, exceeded the 
right of citizens to utilize the democratic process to limit or curtail their 
financial obligations to people illegally residing in our country."
<P>
The judge's ruling is just the most recent example of judicial usurpation 
in what has become "a frontal assault on citizenship and the exercise of 
self-rule," says Roberts. "It demeans citizenship by eliminating any 
difference between the claims of citizens and illegal aliens to taxpayer-
provided benefits. And it destroys self-rule by denying citizens the right 
to limit their taxpaying responsibilities through the exercise of the 
democratic process."
<P>
Judges have been undermining citizenship and self-rule for decades. 
Roberts cites a 1982 Supreme Court decision in which five of the nine 
justices "decided that the State of Texas could not restrict the use of its 
limited resources to educate only lawful residents. The court's cavalier 
disregard of the rights of U.S. citizens was not based on any law or legal 
precedent," says Roberts. "It rested entirely on the subjective feelings of 
five justices that it was good social policy for taxpayers to be made to 
finance public education for illegal aliens."
<P>
Roberts notes that Chief Justice Warren Burger and the three other 
dissenting justices "criticized their brethren for violating the separation of 
powers by assuming a policymaking role. The Constitution, they said, 
does not vest the court with 'the authority to strike down laws because 
they do not meet our standards of desirable social policy."' That's exactly 
what the High Court did and got away with, however, thereby 
demonstrating "how readily blackrobed social engineers substitute their 
own policy predilections for the will of the people."
<P>
Judicial decisions "based on feelings and not law" are unworthy of our 
respect, says Roberts. "If Americans are to be ruled by sociology, we 
have no need of law schools. There is nothing in a legal background to 
give jurists guidance on the 'correct' social policy," and every judge who 
oversteps himself in this manner should be swiftly censured. "The 
elevation of social engineering above law and self-rule has dire 
implications," says Roberts, noting that it may now be plausible for 
illegal aliens to resist deportation by claiming the rights of citizenship. 
This much is clear: no republic can survive without respect for the rule of 
law. When the personal agendas of powerful men replace objective 
standards, when emotion usurps reason, our God-given rights cease to be 
secure and we can no longer rely on the truth and the law to defend 
ourselves from injustice.
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
