<html>
<head>

<title>Duplantier: "Conservative" Clinton  -- 03/04/96</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 4, 1996 <br></i>

<h2>
Conservative Clinton
</h2>

<P>  
<blockquote><i>"The era of big government is over. We know big government does not have all the answers. There is not a program for every problem."</i></blockquote> 
<P>
  
Who was that man who gave the 1996 State of the Union address? He  
looked like Bill Clinton, but he sounded like Ronald Reagan -- until he got  
down to particulars. Then the New Democrat turned back into an Old  
Democrat, and we found out that the era of big government isn't over after  
all, but just playing possum. President Clinton thinks that big government  
still has all the answers, and a program for every problem. Unfortunately,  
the answers are wrong, and the programs just make the problems worse. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;President Clinton still wants to socialize the health care industry -- the  
biggest big-government power grab in decades! In a fit of false  
compassion, he would force actuaries to ignore the hard reality of risk and  
insure the uninsurable, thereby bankrupting yet another vital American  
industry. The President wants to expand federal authority by calling for  
"community partnerships with local police forces" and the investigation of  
local gangs by federal agencies. He declared that "we must end the deadly  
scourge of domestic violence." But whom did he mean by we? Big  
government, of course. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The President insisted that "every classroom in America must be connected  
to the information superhighway, with computers, good software, and well- 
trained teachers." But who's going to do the connecting? And who's going  
to pay for this "technology initiative"? Why, a "national partnership," of  
course. That's another pretext for federal intervention in areas reserved to  
the states by our U.S. Constitution! Clinton wants local schools to adopt  
"national standards," but the federal government has neither the authority  
to establish such standards, nor the integrity to resist politicizing them.  
Clinton called for more federal spending for his national service program,  
cash grants to top high school graduates, expansion of the student loan  
program, and a so-called "GI Bill for America's Workers." That doesn't  
sound like cutting back big government. 
 

 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



President Clinton also called for more taxpayer spending for "drug  
education," even though the $2 billion of federal funds squandered so far  
have had no measurable impact on drug abuse. He asserted that all schools  
should teach "character education: good values and good citizenship." Will  
the federal government establish national character standards, too? Will  
these standards be as far removed from right reason and reality as were the  
outrageous U.S. History Standards? Doesn't Bill Clinton know that the best  
way to teach values is by example? The President even went so far as to  
recommend uniforms for schoolchildren. The era of big government is  
clearly not over when the nation's chief executive officer is preoccupied  
with such local concerns. 
 

 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



No, the era of big government is not over yet, but the era of defending it  
certainly is. Bill Clinton's desperate bid to recast himself as a conservative  
is a tacit admission that liberalism is philosophically bankrupt. 
<p><p>
<hr>




<P><i>

Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:  
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105

</i>

<P> 

