<head>

<title>Duplantier: Religion in America -- 03/07/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc. <br>

<a href="duplio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


March 7, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Religion in America
</h2>



<P><blockquote><i> Millions of Americans are enjoying better health and happier lives than  
they ever imagined, and you can too, once you know the secret. </i></blockquote>
<P> 

Are you suffering from high blood pressure? Does someone in your family  
show signs of depression or substance abuse? Has the fire gone out of your  
married life? Don't despair. Now there's a fast, safe, and simple way to  
overcome these problems -- and it won't cost you an arm and a leg. Sound  
too good to be true? Well, it's not.


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


 
Patrick Fagan of the Heritage Foundation reveals that going to church is  
the secret to better health and a happier life. In a new report called Why  
Religion Matters, Fagan argues that religious practice "strengthens  
individuals, families, communities, and society as a whole. It significantly  
affects educational and job attainment and reduces the incidence of such  
major social problems as out-of-wedlock births, drug and alcohol  
addiction, crime, and delinquency." 
 



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

 
Research indicates that church attendance and good cheer go together.  
"Happiness is greater and psychological stress is lower for those who  
attend religious services regularly," notes Fagan. Less stress means better  
health, of course, but the benefits don't stop there. Church attendance also  
leads to happier, longer-lasting marriages. "Regular church attendance is  
the critical factor in marital stability," says Fagan. Even among those who  
have separated from their partners, "reconciliation rates are higher among  
regular church attendees." 
 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


But wait, there's more. "One of the most powerful of all factors in  
preventing out-of-wedlock births is the regular practice of religious belief,  
[which] sharply reduces the incidence of premarital intercourse. The  
reverse is also true," says Fagan. "The absence of religious practice  
accompanies sexual permissiveness and premarital sex." 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



Still not convinced? What if we told you that "alcohol abuse is 300 percent  
higher among those who do not attend church"? It's true. Not only that, but  
"alcoholics with a religious background or strong religious beliefs are  
much more likely to seek help and treatment." What about suicide? "The  
practice of religion reduces the rate of suicide," says Fagan, more  
effectively than anything else. "Those who attend church frequently are  
four times less likely to commit suicide than those who never attend."  
Church attendance also reduces the incidence of depression, before it can  
lead to suicide. Adolescents are particularly at risk for depression, but they  
"tend to experience fewer anxieties of growing up if they are religious." 
 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;




Patrick Fagan concludes that "regular religious practice is both an  
individual and social good. It is a powerful answer to many of our most  
significant social problems." Going to church is "good for individuals,  
families, states, and the nation. It improves health, learning, economic  
well-being, self-control, self-esteem, and empathy. It reduces the incidence  
of social pathologies, such as out-of-wedlock births, crime, delinquency,  
drug and alcohol addiction, health problems, anxieties, and prejudices."  
So, don't delay. Take advantage of this amazing opportunity now. For a  
happier, healthier life, go to church regularly. 








<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>
 
 
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:  
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i>

<P> 
</blockquote></blockquote>

