<head>

<title>Duplantier: The Future of Education -- 03/08/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEALINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="duplio.html">F.R. Duplantier
</a><br>


March 8, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>The Future of Education

</h2>



<P><blockquote><i>    
The political correctness movement has captured America's universities, and the NEA dominates our    
public school system. But students won't have to learn in lock step much longer, because the technological    
revolution will soon make these institutions of indoctrination obsolete.</i></blockquote>
<p>    
    
Years ago, many Americans got their education from correspondence courses. Now, an enterprising outfit    
in Springfield, Virginia has updated the concept for the '90s. The Teaching Company offers more than 60    
college-level courses on audio and video cassettes. One of their more popular offerings is a 70-part series    
of 45-minute lectures entitled The Great Minds of the Western Intellectual Tradition. Two well-known    
and respected scholars from prestigious Ivy League universities deliver most of the lectures, with four    
other "superstar teachers" supplying the balance. "The result," according to a full-page advertisement in a    
popular weekly magazine, "is a definitive survey of Western thought by an all-star teaching team with no    
equal in lecturing skill at any single college campus anywhere in the world."    



  



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


  
What could be better than access to "an all-star teaching team" on videocassettes at a fraction of the cost    
of college tuition? How about a give-and-take between you and a noted scholar in the privacy of your own    
home? That's available now, too -- thanks to Bob Jones University and something called the Live    
Interactive Network Classroom, or LINC for short. The Live Interactive Network Classroom can be in    
your living room or in a traditional schoolroom -- or in any other private or public facility. No matter    
where you are, you'll receive daily satellite transmissions from a teacher in a television studio -- a teacher    
you can see and hear and speak to, as can any other student anywhere in the country who happens to be    
participating in the same class.



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


     
    
Who's the intended target of this satellite schooling service? Surely not the nation's elite. "The wealthy    
will always be able to afford the best private education," writes syndicated columnist Cal Thomas. In a    
recent column describing the Live Interactive Network Classroom, Thomas argues that LINC "can free the    
middle class, and especially the poor, from their bondage to government schools. As an all-in-one    
resource, it can maintain the highest standards in foreign languages, math, and science, as well as    
advanced subjects, such as physics, that are not always available in private education." Cal Thomas    
predicts that LINC "could eventually allow all parents the freedom to choose what they believe is best for    
their children, at a reasonable price, and without the indoctrination that passes for education in the current    
intellectually and spiritually closed system" that all taxpayers must subsidize whether they want to or not. 



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

   
    
If the Teaching Company and the Live Interactive Network Classroom developed by Bob Jones University    
are any indication of what education will be like in the future, American students have every reason to    
rejoice. American educators, on the other hand, had better start looking for new jobs.    
<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to    
the preservation of our freeenterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free    
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to- America's Future, 7800    
Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.    

</i>

<P>
