<html>
<head>

<title>Duplantier: Whole Language Supporter Recants  -- 03/12/96</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


March 12,  1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Whole Language Supporter Recants
</h2>
<Blockquote><i>

If a child hasn't learned to read by the end of the first grade, he's been  
cheated, and the odds are that he'11 never achieve his true potential.</blockquote></i>

<P>   
Bill Honig was State Superintendent of Public Instruction for California  
from 1983 to 1993. During that decade, he presided over a school system  
that threw out many of the proven pedagogical approaches of the past. The  
test scores for California's public school students plummeted as a direct  
result of this ill-advised change in direction. That's the bad news. The good  
news is that Bill Honig learned from this needless disaster, and maybe his  
testimony will help keep other superintendents of education from making  
the same mistake. 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Bill Honig has written a book called Teaching Our Children to Read. In it,  
he emphasizes that educators must ensure that all schoolchildren are  
"reading beginning books by mid-first grade" and be prepared to resort to  
"organized intervention" for those who aren't. Children who are not  
beginning to read by this point, says Honig, "almost never recover." To  
read successfully, children must learn how to break words into their  
smallest "sound chunks. " In other words, they must master phonics. Honig  
argues that "the amount of time a student is engaged in phonics instruction  
is highly predictive of subsequent reading achievement." 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The former state superintendent of education does not acknowledge his  
own mistake in allowing the destructive Whole Language method to  
become entrenched in state schools during his tenure. Nevertheless, he  
asserts emphatically that children will learn to read only if they are taught  
to sound out the syllables of the English language and put them together  
like building blocks -- not by using pictures to guess at words, as  
recommended by Whole Language advocates. Honig explains that "bad  
habits of guessing" make learning to read much more difficult, and argues  
that "beginning readers who rely too heavily on contextual clues, such as  
pictures or the connection of other words in the passage, are distracted  
from looking at the letters in a word and connecting those letter patterns to  
words in their minds."<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Honig's rejection of the Whole Language approach should have  
tremendous impact on his colleagues throughout the country because of the  
prestigious position Honig once held in California. Unfortunately, the  
ineffective Whole Language approach to reading has driven phonics out of  
most of our nation's school systems. Honig reports that "very few  
instructional programs currently in use provide children with materials  
designed specifically to connect with systematic and sequenced skills  
development. In some cases," he says, "state, county, district, or university  
leaders are overtly or subtly antagonistic to the skills components and  
discourage phonics teaching." Maybe Bill Honig's new book will persuade  
some of these ideologues to take an honest look at the damage they're  
doing with the Whole Language approach. Maybe some of them will  
resolve to teach America's schoolchildren how to read the right way --  
using the proven method of systematic phonics. 
 
<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i> 
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our freeenterprise  
system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of  
this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's  
Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i>
</blockquote></blockquote>
