<head>

<title>Duplantier: Self-Reliance -- 03/13/96</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F. R. Duplantier

</a><br>


March 13,  1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Self-Reliance
</h2><blockquote><i>

If displaced workers spent as much time looking for new jobs as they do complaining about having lost  
their old ones, they'd find themselves employed again much faster. 

</blockquote></i>
<P> 
Bill Prince was merchandising director for Frito-Lay in Dallas from 1959 to 1966, a period during which  
sales skyrocketed from $50 million a year to $325 million. When Frito-Lay merged with Pepsi Cola,  
however, Bill resigned to start his own food company. Despite an enormous personal investment of time,  
money, and his own considerable experience, the company failed, and Bill was obliged to start all over  
again. 
 

 



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 
It wasn't the first time he'd been in that predicament, nor would it be the last. Much like Sisyphus, the  
character in Greek mythology whose fate it was forever to roll a giant rock up a steep hill only to have it  
roll down again every time he reached the top, Bill knew from personal experience that life is a series of  
challenges. Whether you succeed or fail in any given challenge, there's always another giant rock waiting  
to be rolled up another steep hill. 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Bill Prince worked ceaselessly throughout his life, in a wide variety of occupations. Over the course of a  
50-year career, he was never unemployed for more than a month at a time. "Some of the time, my income  
was in the top five percent, but not always," Bill recalls, "because I took any job I could get when I needed  
work." 
 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Bill notes that in recent years many companies have had to downsize in order to survive. This trend has  
been accompanied by increasing numbers of people "complaining about those mean, nasty, uncaring  
corporations and businesses who fire good and loyal workers." Bill wonders if these carpers and grousers  
"really believe" that a company has a lifetime obligation to anyone it hires, "no matter what kind of  
problems the company may have in the future?" He marvels at the attitude so prevalent among displaced  
workers that the government should "do something to save them." They obviously don't understand that  
government intervention is the main reason their jobs have evaporated. Why can't they see, as Bill so  
clearly does, that, "if government had not been passing all those business-busting laws and writing  
harassing, anti-business regulations, they might still have their jobs?" 
 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

"Whatever happened to individual initiative and enterprise?" Bill asks. "And why do people turn to  
government like they are asking for manna from heaven?" Bill insists that middle-aged managers thrown  
back into the job market have no one but themselves to blame if they prefer to remain idle rather than  
accept a job they consider beneath them. "Maybe the reason many downsized people are downsized is  
because they simply no longer have the drive, ambition, and creative ability to withstand competition from  
younger, hungrier people," he speculates in the February issue of a monthly newsletter called Bill's  
Soapbox -- written, edited, and published by Bill Prince himself, at the ripe young age of 74! 
 


<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to  
the preservation of our freeenterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's Future, 7800  
Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i></blockquote></blockquote>

