<head>

<title>Duplantier: The Point of Punishment -- 03/15/96</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


March 15, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
The Point of Punishment
</h2>



<P><blockquote><i>  
Most Americans believe that our criminal justice system works pretty well,  
and that punishments meted out to criminals generally fit the crime. Some  
liberal critics, however, hold a very different view of crime and  
punishment. 
</blockquote></i>
<P>


Some sophisticated liberals believe that "America is an oppressive, racist  
society, and prisons are a none-too-subtle way of subjugating the nation's  
poor and minority populations," say criminologists Charles Logan and  
John Dilulio. In an essay titled "Ten Deadly Myths About Crime and  
Punishment in the U.S.," published in a new book called Criminal Justice:  
The Legal System vs. Individual Responsibility, Logan and Dilulio insist  
that "there is simply no empirical evidence to support the view that  
African-Americans, or the members of other racial and ethnic minorities in  
the U.S., are far more likely than whites" to suffer the legal consequences  
of criminal actions. Differences in conviction rates and sentencing, they  
say, are determined by "such mundane factors as the amount of evidence  
against a defendant, and whether or not a credible eyewitness testified." 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Logan and Ditulio also rebut the common misconception that our prisons  
are "prohibitively expensive." They contend that "it is morally myopic, and  
conceptually and empirically moronic, to argue that public money spent on  
prisons and prisoners is public money wasted." They concede that, "if the  
typical offender committed only one petty property crime per year, then  
paying thousands and thousands of dollars to keep him confined would be  
a bad social investment. But, if he committed a dozen serious property or  
violent crimes each year, then the social benefits of keeping him  
imprisoned might well exceed the social costs of not doing so." Logan and  
DiIulio cite one study that calculated a "social cost" of $430,000 per year  
for a felon left at large -- roughly twenty times what it costs to keep him  
incarcerated. That figure may be overstated, but the fact remains that it is  
far less expensive for society to imprison a felon than to let him roam free. 



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
  
The biggest myth or misconception of all, say Logan and DiIulio, is that  
"punishment itself is inherently wrong. It is largely because they are  
opposed to punishment generally and to imprisonment in particular that  
many people argue so strongly that we must address the root causes of  
crime, that our criminal justice system discriminates, that we are overly  
punitive and haven't considered alternatives, that prisons are too costly and  
overcrowded, and that we must look to the courts for reform." Logan and  
DiIulio see punishment as a positive good, however, one that "affirms  
important moral and cultural values. Legal punishment," they insist, "is a  
legitimate and . . . even a noble aspect of our culture." 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
  

Logan and DiIulio reject "the false dichotomy between punishment and  
'humanitarianism."' They argue that punishment, properly and fairly  
applied, is essential to the treatment of people "as human beings, rather  
than as objects. Punishment," they say, "is an affirmation of the autonomy,  
responsibility, and dignity of the individual." 
 



<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our freeenterprise  
system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of  
this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's  
Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i></blockquote></blockquote>

