<head>
<title>Duplantier:  New-Contract With America     -- 3/18/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 18, 1996   
<br></i>

<h2>New-Contract With America</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
"How has a nation conceived in liberty and opposition to tyranny arrived    
at a point today where citizens are more fearful of their own government    
threatening their rights than they are of any other government?" A    
firebrand freshman Congressman answers his own question.  
</i></blockquote>
<P>     
"Americans deeply believe in the principles of America, but they don't    
see [those principles] reflected in their government," observes freshman    
Republican Representative Sam Brownback of Kansas in the March issue    
of Policy Review. ''Americans believe in freedom, democracy, moral    
values, family, community, and free markets," says Brownback. "Yet    
their government seizes their rights without their consent. Government    
has become their master, not their servant. " Brownback is a staunch    
proponent of the three R's: Reducing, Reforming, and Returning. He says    
we should reduce the size of the federal government, reform Congress,    
and return to "the basic values that built the country: work and family    
and the recognition of a higher moral authority."   
  <p>
In a frenzy of false compassion, our once-limited government "now tries    
to do all things for all people," Brownback observes, arguing that it fails miserably in this task. "We have discovered, by spending trillions of
dollars and taking rights and freedoms away from individuals, that    
government cannot solve all of our problems." The American people    
believe, and rightly so, that "they can handle most of their problems    
better than the federal government can."   
<p>   
If we return to our original principles of limited government, "then our    
nation, our economy, our liberties, and our social fiber will grow    
stronger than we have seen for a generation," predicts Brownback. The    
Congressman from Kansas contends that Americans must "look first to    
themselves and to each other for help," rather than rely on their elected 
representatives. He calls for the restoration of "the master-servant    
relationship between the people and the government," acknowledging    
that many of his colleagues need to be reminded that they hold the    
subordinate position. They also need to be reminded that the powers of    
the federal government are strictly limited by our Constitution.    
Observing that there is "no constitutional basis" for most of the federal 
government's current activities, Brownback argues that it is time to "re-   
limit our federal government so it can perform its proper functions well, 
and leave to the people and the states those functions which the federal    
government was never intended to perform."   
<p>   
Brownback calls for "a new Contract with America -- one that passes    
laws, not merely proposes them." Brownback's Contract would reduce    
federal spending "from 22 percent of our Gross Domestic Product to 15    
percent or less," restrict the tax code to the raising of revenue and    
"remove all social engineering" from it, cut the number of cabinet    
agencies from 14 to no more than nine "and restrict their regulatory    
powers under constitutional principles," require the citation of "precise  constitutional authority" for all proposed legislation, and eliminate all
government interference in private charity. Sounds like a pretty good    
contract. Where do we sign?  
  
<P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit    
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our    
free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a    
free transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. </i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
