<head>
<title>Duplantier:  MEDICAL SAVINGS ACCOUNTS  -- 3/22/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 22, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Medical Savings Accounts</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
Health care spending today is more than twenty times what it was in    
1965. The primary reason for that dramatic increase is the third-party    
payment system. 
</i></blockquote>
<p>   
Research analyst Peter Barwick of the Commonwealth Foundation in    
Harrisburg, Pennsylvania argues that "people are never as careful in    
spending someone else's money as they are in spending their own." This    
simple fact of human nature is what's behind the spiraling cost of health    
care in America. "Between 1965 and 1995, total annual spending on    
health care in the U.S. rose from $41.6 billion to $938.3 billion in    
constant dollars," reports Barwick. "This dramatic increase in health care    
spending coincided with a sharp rise in third-party payment." The    
Pennsylvania researcher estimates that "79 cents of every dollar used to    
purchase health care is paid by someone other than the person receiving    
treatment."   
<p>   
Barwick sees a direct link "between rising health care costs and the    
increase in third-party payment." He argues that there is little incentive    
for economizing "when people only have to pay 21 cents to get a dollar's    
worth of coverage." When patients don't care how much a particular    
medicine or treatment will cost, "physicians and other medical    
professionals will have little reason to seek the most cost-effective ways    
to provide quality care."   
<p>   
The solution, Barwick believes, is Medical Savings Accounts (known as    
an MSAs), which provide "the individual consumer with the resources    
needed to pay directly for ordinary health care expenditures, together    
with the incentive to do so responsibly." Barwick describes MSAs as    
"tax-free accounts into which individuals may deposit money to be used    
to pay for everyday health care needs. Typically," he says, "MSAs are    
combined with a catastrophic insurance policy which covers all health    
care expenses beyond a high fixed deductible."   
<p>   
Barwick argues that "MSAs provide health care consumers with a strong    
incentive to conserve resources, since the consumer gets to keep whatever    
cost-savings he is able to achieve. By encouraging frugality among    
consumers, MSAs would also provide incentive to physicians and other    
health care professionals to utilize the most costeffective means of    
providing quality care." Barwick notes that other proposed health care    
reforms "seek to regulate patients, physicians, and hospitals more heavily,    
resulting in restrictions on the freedom of the patient to choose a    
physician and [the freedom] of the physician to select the type of    
treatment to be used. In contrast, MSAs leave these choices where they    
belong: in the hands of individual health care recipients and their    
physicians."   
<p>   
In addition to providing patients and doctors with an incentive to save,    
MSAs would reduce administrative costs, which account for as much as    
25 percent of health care spending. They would also reduce out-of-pocket    
expenses for "the vast majority of health care recipients." And they would    
solve the portability problem by allowing employees to "take any unspent    
MSA funds with them when leaving a job."   

 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




