<head>
<title>Duplantier:  World Trade Organization  -- 3/26/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 26, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>World Trade Organization</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
The World Trade Organization's recent ruling against the United States     
is a taste of things to come -- unless American voters can persuade their     
Congressmen to abrogate the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade     
and say no to the New World Order.
</i></blockquote>
<P>     
    

    
The World Trade Organization's recent ruling against the United States     
is a taste of things to come -- unless American voters can persuade their     
Congressmen to abrogate the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade     
and say no to the New World Order.    
<p>    
The jig is up. The internationalists have jumped the gun. They've shown     
their hand too soon. And now their legislative lackeys in the U.S.     
Congress are obliged, in the middle of an election year, to defend the     
indefensible. Having sworn to uphold the Constitution and protect the     
sovereignty of the United States, they must now figure out a way to     
justify their support for a treaty that undermines both -- or resign     
themselves to humiliating defeats in November.    
<p>    
Congress ratified the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (known as     
GATT) during its lame-duck session in December 1994. That treaty     
established the World Trade Organization ( known as WTO) and gave it     
the power to settle trade disputes among signatory nations. Well, lo and     
behold, the WTO, in its first major decision, has ruled against the United     
States! The Members of Congress who ratified the treaty knew that such     
an outcome was a distinct possibility. It was widely predicted at the time.     
Nevertheless, they willingly voted to subject the economic, social, and     
legislative decisions of American citizens to the whims of an international     
tribunal.    
<p>    
What that international tribunal did was to order the United States to     
change its rules on the quality of imported gasoline or face sanctions     
against U.S. industries. The governments of Venezuela and Brazil had     
appealed to the World Trade Organization to compel the U.S. to accept     
their gasoline, which does not meet U.S. environmental standards.     
Congress will now have to revise our Clean Air Act regulations regarding     
gasoline emissions or U.S. industries will face "cross-retaliation" trade     
sanctions. Since the United States does not export gasoline to Venezuela     
or Brazil, there is no direct way to exact revenge on U.S. petroleum     
interests. So, in the name of "free trade," the WTO will probably order     
trade sanctions against other U.S. industries that are wholly unrelated to     
the gasoline industry or the EPA regulations.    
<p> 
Now, Democrats and Republicans both have egg on their faces. President     
Clinton promised his liberal supporters in 1994 that the WTO would     
never undercut our environmental regulations. The Republican leadership     
in Congress promised their conservative backers that American     
sovereignty would not be endangered by the agreement. Well, it turns out     
they were both mistaken, or less than candid.    
<p>    
William Gill of the American Coalition for Competitive Trade considers     
the recent WTO ruling truly ominous. Gill and his group tried to warn     
Members of Congress that the North American Free Trade Agreement     
and the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade "were the first big steps     
toward a world government that would rob America of our cherished     
independence as a nation." But our elected representatives just wouldn't     
listen. By the time November 5th rolls around, they may wish they had.    
<P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




