<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier:  UN Tax  -- 3/27/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 27, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>UN Tax</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
The proposal for a global tax to finance the operations of the United   
Nations went over like a lead balloon among average Americans. Many   
of our so-called leaders support the idea, however, seeing it as a   
necessary step on the road to a New World Order.  
</i></blockquote>
<P>         
United Nations Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali thinks the UN   
could be a lot more effective if the world body did not have to answer to   
any of its member nations. If it had its own means of support, and its own   
army, then Boutros-Ghali and his fellow internationalists could give   
orders instead of taking them. The idea makes perfect sense to power-  
hungry globalists, who simply can't understand why it doesn't appeal to   
the citizens of nations expected to sacrifice their sovereignty.  
<p>  
Boutros-Ghali wants to finance the nearly bankrupt United Nations by   
imposing a global tax on foreign exchange transactions. A mere half-of-  
one-percent tax on these transactions would generate an astounding $1.5   
trillion. The Secretary General is willing to consider alternative means of   
raising revenue, of course, such as taxes on international travel, fossil   
fuels, international arms sales, and so on. The important thing is to   
establish an independent revenue source. "It is time to seriously address   
the need for a United Nations that can operate on a secure and steady   
financial foundation," said Boutros-Ghali when he floated his unpopular   
proposal. "I'm sure we will win in the end, and that we will obtain from   
the international community [an understanding] that we need to have our   
own income."  
<p>  
The international community may understand Boutros-Ghali's objectives,   
but so does the average American citizen, and he wants no part of it. "The   
ability to control territory and command an army, like the ability to tax,   
represents the exercise of sovereign power," observes Thomas Sheehy of   
the Heritage Foundation. "The UN should never have this power; it   
would be a usurpation of the constitutional rights of the American people.   
These rights are protected by the U.S. government, not the UN. The UN   
does not represent the interests of Americans; it represents the interests of   
its 185 member states, many of which are undemocratic and repressive."  
<p>  
Sheehy denies that the UN suffers from "a lack of funding. In fact," he   
says, "UN spending has been mushrooming, and that is the real problem."   
Still, the UN wants more. "In September 1996, the UN Working Group   
on Finances will submit a report on financing to the UN General   
Assembly," observes Sheehy. "This report may very well recommend a   
UN tax scheme." Sheehy notes that legislation has been introduced in   
both houses of the U.S. Congress to prohibit U.S. compliance with UN   
efforts to implement a tax. He argues that "the last thing the UN needs is   
more money and less accountability." The real question, however, is what   
America needs: We need leaders who will respect and protect our nation's   
sovereignty. The best way to do that is by withdrawing from the United   
Nations and expelling this would-be world government from our shores.  
<P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




