<html>
<head>

<title>Duplantier: ENVIRONMENTALISM -- 4/9/96</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


April 9, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
ENVIRONMENTALISM
</h2>



<P><blockquote><i>  
"By the end of the 1980s, environmental bills accounted for nearly one-
fifth of bills presented to Congress and almost one-quarter of those 
enacted into law."
</blockquote></i>
<P>



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
                            
"The government's environmental activism has been costly," writes 
Jonathan Adler of the Competitive Enterprise Institute. "The 
Environmental Protection Agency has estimated that Americans spend 
well over $150 billion per year complying with environmental 
regulations." In a new book called Environmentalism at the Crossroads, 
published by the Capital Research Center, Adler argues that businesses 
trying to absorb the costs of compliance "are likely to pass on the cost to 
consumers by raising the price of their products. And, when they are 
confronted by the uncertainties of statutory interpretation and the 
regulatory enforcement of environmental law, they may decide to slow 
the development and application of new technologies."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The cost of environmental regulation continues to increase, even as more 
and more Americans are questioning its effectiveness, "particularly in the 
area of risk reduction." Adler contends that "attempting to improve 
environmental quality in one area can hurt the environment in other 
areas." Even worse, regulations can sometimes have an effect quite the 
opposite of what was intended, as has happened with the Endangered 
Species Act. Adler notes that "landowners lose the right to use their land 
as they see fit when an endangered animal is discovered on it. 
Landowners cannot build or enlarge their homes, plant crops, or cut down 
trees. Rather than protect wildlife, the Endangered Species Act punishes 
landowners, in effect, for creating or maintaining a species habitat. The 
Act creates disincentives for protecting endangered species," says Adler, 
with the result that "landowners who find an endangered species on their 
property may well decide to destroy it and its habitat before it's 
discovered by federal authorities."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Adler asserts that "many policy experts and the public now recognize the 
failings of much environmental policy." Nevertheless, he says, 
"Washington's environmental lobbies are unyielding." They know that 
regulatory reform is needed to establish accurate methods of risk 
assessment, proscribe unfunded mandates, and protect private property 
rights, but they refuse to admit it. Rather than harness the time-tested 
incentives of the free enterprise system in the service of their mission, 
they remain blindly committed to government intervention. "Washington 
environmental lobbyists steadfastly oppose risk assessment, relief from 
unfunded mandates, and greater protection of property," Adler observes. 
"Environmentalists do not see that the public's interest in economic 
common sense and fairness is compatible with support for a clean 
environment."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Without meaningful reform, however, regulators will continue to target 
risks that have "public relations or political value," in the process 
spending "millions of dollars that do comparatively little to improve 
public health and environmental quality." They will continue to impose 
unfunded mandates on state and local governments, with the result that 
"local priorities must be subordinated to Washington's dictates." And they 
will continue to issue environmental regulations that "override private 
land-use decisions," thereby violating the "takings clause" of the Fifth 
Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.


<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise  
system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of  
this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's  
Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i></blockquote></blockquote>

