<head>
<title>Duplantier: Flat Tax -- 4/29/96</title>


<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

April 29, 1996 
<br></i>

<h2>Flat Tax </h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
"Americans are tired of our oppressive tax code and they want a new 
system. But to get there, they need an honest and open debate. They're 
not getting it from the politicians and the media."
</i></blockquote>


<P> 
Having recognized that they could no longer ignore the subject of the 
flat tax, the mainstream media have recently resorted to their second-
favorite tactic: misrepresenting the issue. They claim that the flat 
tax will hurt homeowners by eliminating the deduction for mortgage 
interest. They suggest that the flat tax will send philanthropy into a 
free fall by eliminating the deduction for charitable giving. They say 
that the flat tax isn't even a tax cut -- and, if it is, well, then, 
it's a tax cut that favors the rich! 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 Congressman Dick Armey of Texas thinks it's time to set the record 
straight on the flat tax. The House Majority Leader insists that, no 
matter what the media may say, the flat tax is indeed a tax cut: "With 
a flat tax the middle class will pay less in taxes, their wages will 
increase, and they will keep more of what they earn to save and invest 
in their families." If that's not a tax cut, what is it? 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The media attempt to foment class envy, but that doesn't change the 
fact that the flat tax does indeed tax investment income. "What it 
doesn't do," says Armey, "is tax it twice." Businesses will continue 
to pay taxes under a flat tax system. Since corporate income taxes are 
paid, ultimately, by investors, the current tax on investment income 
is actually a second tax on the same income. "Under a flat tax," says 
Armey, "all income, including investment income, is taxed once and 
only once." Why should investors be required, as they are now, to pay 
tax on income that's already been taxed? 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The media resort to scare tactics to unnerve the middle-class 
mortgage-holder, but the fact remains that "the flat tax is good for 
homeowners." Armey argues that the flat tax will "lower interest 
rates, reduce mortgage payments, and put more money in the pockets of 
working Americans." Lower rates, lower payments, more money left over 
-- how can that be bad? 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The media cynically assume that deductibility drives donations, but 
Armey argues that "the flat tax will not reduce charitable giving. 
Americans don't consult their tax tables and accountants before 
helping their neighbors in need. As our family incomes increase, so 
too will our generosity." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It doesn't matter what the mainstream media say, because the flat tax 
is an idea whose time has come. Congressman Dick Armey maintains that 
the flat tax is "bigger than any politician. It's bigger than any 
political party. And it's bigger than the Washington establishment. It 
belongs to the American people." Armey argues that "class-warfare 
rhetoric" and "narrow, special-interest propaganda" will only delay 
the day of reckoning. "The American people," he says, "deserve an 
open, honest debate on tax reform. Right now." 

 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




