<head>
<title>Duplantier RITALIN -- 5/23/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.</i><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

<I>   
 May 23, 1996  
 </I>
 
<h2>RITALIN</h2>
<P>
<blockquote><I>
  
  
The Chuck E Cheese pizza chain bills itself as the place "where a kid   
can be a kid. " Elementary school used to be such a place, but not   
anymore. Nowadays, when a kid acts like a kid, the public schools   
diagnose him as having an attention deficit or hyperactivity disorder.</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
Remember, when you were a kid, how you never ran out of energy? How   
you could never sit still for more than a few minutes at a time? How your   
mind would race from one subject to the next? How you loved to   
daydream? You had no idea you were suffering from a disease, did you?
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
As many as two million children have been diagnosed as having   
Attention Deficit Disorder or Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder.   
The preferred form of treatment for these alleged disorders is a powerful   
drug called Ritalin -- a Schedule II controlled substance, as are cocaine   
and methadone. The U.S. Department of Education formally recognized   
Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder as a handicap in 1991 and made   
federal funds available for local school districts to provide special   
educational and psychological services for children afflicted with the   
normal characteristics of childhood. 
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
  
Needless to say, many school systems liked having extra cash to play   
with, and were perfectly willing to add special physical and mental   
health programs to their ever-growing menu of services if that was what   
would keep the funds flowing from Washington. Goals 2000 has   
provided a convenient umbrella for new programs in which school health   
officials test children for emotional, social, mental, and physical   
disorders -- and, when they deem it necessary, prescribe and administer   
medications such as Ritalin, Valium, and Prozac. New rules allow nurse   
practitioners and physician assistants to prescribe drugs. Goals 2000   
proposals receive funding from the Department of Education, Medicaid,   
Maternal and Child Health block grants, state programs, and private   
foundations. 
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160&#160; 
  
In 1994, the U.S. Department of Education gave the Chesapeake   
Institute of Washington, D.C. the funding to produce two videos called   
Facing the Challenges of Attention Deficit Disorder and One Child in   
Every Classroom. The completed videos included enthusiastic   
endorsements of Ritalin from parents whose children take the drug. A   
PBS documentary subsequently revealed, however, that these same   
parents were board members of a group called Children and Adults with   
Attention Deficit Disorder, which has received cash grants of $900,000   
plus in-kind services from the manufacturer of Ritalin. John Merrow,   
executive producer of the PBS documentary, reported that Ritalin is now   
so plentiful that a black market has developed on the school playground.   
At many junior high schools, Ritalin is the first drug a child experiments   
with. 
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
  
It's bad enough that the public schools have intentionally dumbed down   
their curricula in order to turn our children into intellectual zombies.   
Now they're pinpointing the kids with energy and spunk and drugging   
them into a state of lethargy. Parents of a child who has been diagnosed   
by school personnel as having Attention Deficit Disorder or Attention   
Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder should seek a second opinion.  
<P>  
   
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit   
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free   
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:   
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</I>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>


