<head>
<title>Duplantier: THE WORKING RICH -- 5/27/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif">
</a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
May 27, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>The Working Rich</h2>


<i><blockquote>


There are many kinds of bigotry in the world, but most of them, in 
America at least, are recognized as morally repugnant. There is one kind 
of bigotry, however, that seems to be socially acceptable -- the irrational 
prejudice against people who are wealthy.
</blockquote></i>

The vast majority of rich people in America acquired their wealth the 
old-fashioned way: they earned it. Industriousness, determination, 
shrewdness, and daring -- these are the qualities they cultivated to 
achieve self-sufficiency and, ultimately, abundance. The relatively few 
Americans fortunate enough to inherit great wealth have had to display 
these same qualities in order to maintain their positions. Nevertheless, it 
is quite common -- among people who are lazy, aimless, dull, and timid -
- to bemoan their unfortunate lot in life and rail against the undeserved 
luck of those who happen to be rich.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Economist and syndicated columnist Thomas Sowell has had enough of 
this nonsense. "Far from being the idle rich, those in the top fifth of 
income-earners work more than most people and far more than those in 
the bottom fifth," says Sowell. "They work more time and they have 
more people in the same family working. When people are putting in 
long hours of work often after having put in long years of schooling, 
followed by long years of building up the skills and experience that put 
them where they are today, we are not talking about lottery winners or 
people who got lucky some other way. We are talking about 
achievement. And we are talking about the kind of work that other 
Americans benefit from."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Sowell cites Bill Gates as one man whose wealth is richly deserved. With 
his innovative computer software products, the Microsoft 
multimillionaire has provided enormous benefits, directly or indirectly, 
to every single American. "The economy is not a zero-sum game, where 
every gain is somebody else's loss," says Sowell. "We are all better off 
because of those [supposedly] 'fortunate' people who work long hours at 
difficult tasks that not everyone is capable of doing."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The generation of wealth generally requires long, hard work. For this 
reason, improved economic standing is usually associated with 
advancing age. The rich and the poor "are often the same people at 
different stages of their careers," says Thomas Sowell. "People in their 
60s have earned far more than people in their 20s, even though everyone 
in his 60s was once 20. This is not an injustice by 'society.' It is a 
reflection of the mundane fact that there is a huge difference in 
competence and efficiency before and after spending years doing what 
you do." Precious few people start out rich, and the vast majority of 
Americans who begin their careers in the bottom fifth in income "are out 
of there before a decade has passed. For one thing," says Sowell, "they 
have 10 years more experience at the end of a decade."

<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
