<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: WELFARE REFORM/PA & OR -- 5/28/96</title>
</head>

           
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">


<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif">
</a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
May 28, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2> Welfare Reform/PA & OR </h2>


<i><blockquote>


Welfare as we know it is not long for this world. State governments all 
across America are redesigning so-called entitlement programs to make 
sure that they promote self-sufficiency rather than dependence.
</blockquote></i>
 
"Over the past five years a new consensus has emerged in the welfare 
debate," reports Peter Barwick of the Commonwealth Foundation in 
Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. "In sharp contrast to the traditional view of 
welfare as an entitlement," says Barwick, "many experts now agree that 
welfare must require work, and that the single most important step that 
can be taken to reform welfare is to impose up-front work requirements 
on all able-bodied recipients. Support for this view comes not from a 
mean-spirited desire to punish welfare recipients, but from a concern to 
help welfare recipients achieve long-term self-sufficiency."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Barwick argues that the welfare reform plan proposed in Pennsylvania 
"falls short in its effort to replace welfare with work. To his credit, the 
Governor insists that welfare recipients work a minimum of twenty hours 
a week in order to receive benefits. Unfortunately, the significance of this 
requirement is vitiated by the fact that it can be satisfied with all sorts of 
substitute activities." Barwick contends that "the Governor's plan gives 
far too much wiggle room to those who would coddle recipients with 
notoriously ineffective and expensive 'education' and 'training' programs, 
or confine them to public-sector make-work programs which fail to give 
participants marketable skills and experience."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


One program that does effectively link welfare to work is Oregon's Full 
Employment model, known as JOBS Plus. This program, Barwick 
explains, "takes the money already allocated for the three largest welfare 
programs -- Aid to Families with Dependent Children, Food Stamps, and 
Unemployment Insurance -- and uses this money instead to subsidize 
jobs for welfare recipients in the private sector." Having proven quite 
successful during its two years as a pilot program, JOBS Plus is now 
being implemented statewide. Barwick notes that Oregon's Full 
Employment model "has been influential in shaping reform in nearly a 
dozen other states to date."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


How does the program work? "Participation in JOBS Plus is required of 
virtually all those who qualify for AFDC, Food Stamps, or 
Unemployment Insurance," observes Peter Barwick. "Participants are 
initially given assistance in finding regular full-time jobs. Those unable 
to find traditional employment are placed in subsidized jobs with private-
sector employers. These employers -- who volunteer for the program and 
have final say in all hiring decisions -- are reimbursed by the state for the 
minimum wage plus the employer's share of Social Security, 
Unemployment Insurance, and Workers' Compensation premiums. 
Subsidized jobs under JOBS Plus are temporary, lasting four months, 
with an optional two-month extension. Employers are free to hire 
satisfactory participants at any time during the process."
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

                                                                           
Poor people crave self-respect just like anyone else. Why not give them a 
chance to achieve it, with welfare reform programs that offer a hand-up 
rather than a handout?
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
