<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: Welfare Reform/IA & SC -- 6/20/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>
          

<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
June 20, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Welfare Reform/IA &SC</h2>
<i><blockquote>
<P>
Iowa and South Carolina offer two examples of innovative   
welfare reform.
</I></Blockquote><P>

"In 1993, the Iowa state legislature enacted a welfare reform   
program designed to help welfare recipients become self-  
sufficient,'' reports Amy Frantz of the Public Interest Institute   
in Mount Pleasant, Iowa. Writing in the May issue of   
Alternatives in Philanthropy, published by the Capital   
Research Center, Frantz relates that Aid to Families with   
Dependent Children (known as AFDC) "was replaced with   
the Family Investment Program [which] provides cash   
benefits to participants based on their assets, income, and   
family size." Participants in the program "must sign a   
contract, called the Family Investment Agreement, in which   
they promise to participate in Iowa's employment program,   
Promise Jobs." The program provides such services as   
"education and job training, resume writing, and [instruction   
in] interviewing techniques."  
  <p>
Participants in the Family Investment Program "must agree to   
meet a timetable for achieving self-sufficiency,'' says Frantz.   
"Those who refuse to sign a Family Investment Agreement   
must enter a Limited Benefit Plan. This pays reduced benefits   
for three months, then terminates all benefits." Under-aged   
parents who have not yet finished high school "must pursue   
their diplomas to receive benefits."  
  <p>
Frantz reports that "Iowa has also created programs that   
allow private organizations to help those in the Family   
Investment Program." Individual Development Accounts, for   
example, "are held by low-income individuals and can be   
used for post-secondary education, the purchase of a home, or   
starting a small business," says Frantz. "In addition to funds   
that individuals contribute to [these accounts], community-  
based organizations can provide matching funds."  
  <p>
Also in the May issue of Alternatives in Philanthropy, Mike   
Hubbard of the South Carolina Policy Council Education   
Foundation in Columbia reports that South Carolina "has   
joined a growing number of states that have enacted major   
welfare reform. Last year, the General Assembly passed the   
Family Independence Act, requiring the South Carolina   
Department of Social Services to reorient its mission from   
distributing welfare checks to helping welfare recipients find   
jobs." The state must obtain "waivers from certain federal   
laws and regulations," however, before it can implement   
some of the proposed reforms. "Unfortunately," says   
Hubbard, "the Clinton administration is fighting the state   
over most of these, delaying the full impact of reform."  
  <p>
The Family Independence Act redefines success for state   
agencies as "a shrinking caseload and an increase in the   
number of recipients placed in jobs," Hubbard continues.   
"Benefits are limited to 24 consecutive months," and new   
applicants for welfare must "prove they have been looking   
for work." South Carolina goes to great lengths to facilitate   
that job search. "The state helps recipients relocate to areas   
with better job opportunities," for example, and offers   
employers "a tax credit for hiring and maintaining   
recipients." The program is practical rather than sentimental,   
however. "Teenage unwed mothers must live with a parent or   
guardian," says Hubbard, and fathers who fail to pay child   
support have their drivers licenses and other sporting and   
professional licenses revoked.  

<P>
<center># # # # #</center>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
