<head>
<title>Behind the Headlines</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </h4>
 <i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
 F.R. Duplantier<br>
 September 22, 1995 <br>
 </i><hr>
<h2>Americorps: Voluntarism?</h2> <br></center>
 
When Congress tried to defund Americorps last year, Democrats accused  
Republicans of wanting to destroy "voluntarism." But what kind of  
voluntarism is it when the volunteer gets paid, and handsomely?  <p>
  
  
High school graduates who defer college for a year and enroll in  
Americorps instead "receive a healthy stipend and a $4,700 voucher for  
college education," reports Robert Sirico, president of the Acton Institute   
for the Study of Religion and Liberty, in a recent newspaper editorial. He  
cites an audit by the General Accounting Office that pegged the cost of  
the 20,000 Americorps "volunteers" at nearly $31.500 each, "which  
works out to be pretty good pay at taxpayers' expense."  <p>
  
Sirico suggests that "voluntarism" may not be the right word for such  
activity. "One view of voluntarism is that it is uncompensated labor," he  
observes. "People volunteer at a soup kitchen or in local service clubs.   
Well, by that definition, Americorps is not voluntary. Eliminate the  
incentives of the stipend and the education voucher and then we'll  
discover just how 'voluntary' the program is." <p> 
  
Sirico is willing to consider other definitions. He notes that voluntarism  
may be construed to mean "doing something because of benevolent  
personal desire," and concedes that Americorps workers may be   
motivated by good intentions. "But this does not set them apart from  
other workers." he insists. "Most entrepreneurs love their work. They also  
desire the happiness of others. They try to give people something they  
want, whether it is a good meal, quality clothing, sturdy housing, or  
reliable letter delivery. Somehow, though, capitalist acts are not supposed  
to qualify as 'voluntary' in this sense."  <p>
  
Suppose "voluntarism" simply means "anything that is not coerced." Still,  
we have a problem. "In a market economy, the jobs of just about  
everyone pass this test. No one is forced to take a job," says Sirico. "Most   
people face an array of alternatives of how to use their talents in the  
market." Sirico insists that "the very existence of our social safety net  
means workers in America volunteer to be responsible people, to earn a   
living by the sweat of their brows."  <p>
  
No, none of these definitions will do. "The only trait of Americorps that  
distinguishes it from charity, jobs, or entrepreneurship in the private  
sector," Sirico concludes, "is that it is sponsored and run by government.   
This seems to be the message of Americorps: You're not really working  
for the social good unless you are working under government guidance."  
Sirico finds this message disturbing. "It teaches young people a false  
notion about trade," he says, the notion being that "working for a  
business, for profit. is somehow ignoble." Americorps "forcibly siphons  
money from the public through taxation" and pays its volunteers "a   
hefty sum" while vaunting its moral superiority. <p> 
  
Sirico has some sage advice for the idealistic youth: "If serving others is  
what you desire, don't be bought off by a government program. Try  
something voluntary that is personally challenging, socially beneficial,   
and doesn't cost the taxpayers one dime."  <p>
  
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St.  
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
