<title>Behind the Headlines</title>
<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>
 Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br> 
 F.R. Duplantier<br>
 September 25, 1995 </i><br><hr>

<h2>Social Experimentation in Americas Armed Forces</h2> </center>
 
Here is a revolting irony for you: Daring young combat pilots feel more 
secure dodging anti-aircraft guns over enemy territory than they do when 
speaking their minds on American soil. <p>
 
 
The temperature can reach 125 degrees on the tarmac at Nellis Air Force 
Base in Nevada, reports Mindy Belz in a recent issue of World magazine. 
"Hotter still," she says, "is the situation of any officer who dares  
to question even in a private conversation, the Clinton administration's 
policies that are undermining the spirit of America's armed forces." Belz 
observes with dismay that the officers at the Air Force Weapons School 
"speak cautiously. even mechanically, about profound changes in the 
military" -- voicing pat approval for such controversial trends as women 
in combat, downsizing of the services, and murky missions under foreign 
command. When the men charged with defending our freedoms have to 
watch everything they say and be constantly on guard against betrayal, 
something is desperately wrong in America. <p>
 
It is true that soldiers must be trained not to question authority. "The 
militarys code of ethics -- taking orders -at its best preserves order and 
strength in the military," Belz concedes. "But the about-face of President 
Clinton (and President Bush before him) on fundamental issues -- such as 
keeping military policy insulated from the fluctuating pop-culture 
influences -- has trickled down without public debate." This is an  
unhealthy situation. It will lead to demoralization of the troops, their 
involvement in social experimentation. and reduced security for our 
country. "Stifling debate on matters that go to the heart of military 
readiness undermines the dutiful," Belz charges. "Political correctness 
turns loyalty into Newspeak." <p>
 
Orders may be orders, but every veteran can remember when giving and 
getting some guff was part of the equation. After all, the right to have his 
own opinion, the right to disagree, was partly what he fought for. Blind 
obedience went out with the Nuremberg trials. Or did it? Belz cites the 
case of Navy Lt. Commander Ken Carkhuff, a 17-year veteran who 
confided to his commanding officer that he had religious objections  
to women in combat. That comment led ultimately to a board of inquiry, 
which recommended separation from the service. Fortunately, public 
opinion persuaded the Secretary of the Navy to overrule the board and  
allow Carkhuff to remain. A high-ranking Air Force officer who prefers 
to remain nameless says that criticizing the concept of women in combat 
is "a career-ender." <p>
 
Belz points out that "the Senate continues to hold the power of conferring 
rank on all military officers,'' and that feminist senators "have attacked 
the retirement grade of three Navy admirals . . . who were accused of  
not promoting women." This is America? Men who spent their entire 
lives in service must now kowtow to these feminist bullies or risk 
jeopardizing the benefits they have earned. Can this be the country they  
fought for? <p>
 
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free 
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. 
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
