<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Lynne Cheney visits Discovery</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H3><I>From the Fall 1995 Discovery Journal:</I></H3>
<H1><CENTER>Lynne Cheney tells Seattle the Truth </CENTER>
</H1>
<BR>
&quot;The idea that truth is something to be invented rather than pursued,&quot;
Lynne Cheney writes in her new book <I>Telling the Truth</I>, &quot;has
passed beyond narrow academic circles to influence many fields of endeavor&quot;
including: education, historical writing, journalism, psychology and even
politics. <BR>
<BR>
Cheney, former Chair of the National Endowment for the Humanities, will
speak about the importance of truth and what we can do restore it, at a
Seattle luncheon sponsored by CityClub and Discovery Institute. <BR>
<BR>
Cheney's book, subtitled <I>Why Our Culture and Our Country Have Stopped
Making Sense-and What We Can Do About It</I>, is elevating the level of
debate about truth and society all over the nation. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Some of us think of Lynne Cheney as a highly decorated veteran-many
ribbons for heroic service, and some purple hearts-of the culture wars,&quot;
said columnist George Will. &quot;This book is a vivid report from the war's
many fronts.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
If you'd like to hear Cheney's thoughts on Telling the Truth, call (206)
682-7395 for information and to reserve your seat. The luncheon is Thursday,
November 16, 12 noon - 1:30 p.m. at the downtown Seattle Sheraton Hotel
and the cost is $25. <BR>
<HR>
