<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Educational Affairs -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">M</FONT>arketing</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>Educational Affairs</B></CENTER><P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
On April 27, Heritage Vice President for Educational Affairs <a href="/heritage/staff/meyerson.htm">Adam Meyerson</a> 
was a guest lecturer at Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of Government. 
 According to former Congressman Mickey Edwards, who had organized the curriculum, 
Meyerson's class was rated by the students as one of the course's highlights. 
        
<p>
Though many in the academic community remain openly hostile to conservative 
ideas, The Heritage Foundation's academic outreach programs are attempting 
to break the left's hold on academia. Activities include the Bradley Scholars 
Program, Salvatori Center for Academic Leadership, Resource Bank, and Lectures 
and Seminars.
<p>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">B</FONT>radley <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>cholars</H3></CENTER>
<p>
The Bradley Scholars Program, made possible by a grant from the Lynde and Harry 
Bradley Foundation of Milwaukee, welcomed its eighth class to Washington in 
September: crime reporter <a href="/heritage/staff/carlson.htm">Tucker Carlson</a>, a former Policy Review Assistant 
Editor, who rejoined Heritage after a year as an editorial writer for the Democrat-Gazette 
in Little Rock; <a href="/heritage/staff/toler.htm">Herbert H. Toler, Jr.</a>, an expert on the black church in America, 
who joined Heritage from Union Theological Seminary and Howard University; 
and <a href="/heritage/staff/hood.htm">John Hood</a>, Vice President of the John Locke Foundation, Raleigh, N.C., 
a prominent state think tank.
<p>
The Bradley Scholars Program provides writers and academics with a venue in 
Washington for conducting long-term research and writing projects geared to 
current public policy issues.
<p>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>alvatori 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>enter</H3></CENTER>
<p>
Forty college and university faculty members and advanced graduate students 
were named Heritage Foundation Salvatori Fellows in 1994.
<p>

Focus of the Salvatori Center's Annual Conference for Academic Leadership, 
held May 11-12, was "The Constitution of Ordered Liberty: Academic Questions 
for the 21st Century."  More than 100 scholars, academic administrators, and 
journalists attended the conference. The annual Salvatori Awards for Academic 
Excellence were presented to Henry Manne, George Mason University School of 
Law, Fairfax, VA, and Edward Banfield, Harvard University.
<p>
Heritage's Salvatori Center for Academic Leadership was established in 1991 
to encourage academic excellence and stimulate the study and discussion in 
higher education of the ideas and principles that form the foundations of America's 
political and cultural traditions. Salvatori Center programs are made possible 
by a grant from the Henry Salvatori Foundation of Los Angeles.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>esource <FONT SIZE = "+2">B</FONT>ank</H3></CENTER>

The "networking" arm of Heritage's Educational Affairs program, the <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/rtoc.html">Resource 
Bank</a> is a cooperative exchange program involving more than 2,000 university 
professors, academic research centers, educational foundations, and policy 
groups in the United States and abroad. The purpose of the Resource Bank, which 
was established in 1977, is to help conservative scholars and policy specialists 
participate more fully in the policy-making process.
<p>

Some 300 Resource Bank members from a record 130 organizations attended the 
17th Annual Resource Bank Meeting in Chicago in April. The theme of the two-day 
conference was "Restoring the American Community: The `New Citizenship' at 
Work," a phrase coined by Bradley Foundation President Michael Joyce to describe 
the rebirth of grassroots activism around the country.  The program highlighted 
the efforts of volunteers, activists, entrepreneurs, and citizen-legislators.
<p>
The Resource Bank's working groups focused in 1994 on state issues, public 
interest law, unfunded federal mandates, family issues, and foreign and defense 
policy issues.
<p>
<CENTER><a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/95lect.htm"><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">L</FONT>ectures and <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>eminars</H3></a></CENTER>
<p>
What do film critic Michael Medved, Chief of Naval Operations Admiral Jeremy 
Boorda, Americans for Tax Reform President Grover Norquist, and the Ambassadors 
of Argentina, Brazil, Ecuador, and Mexico have in common? They all spoke at 
The Heritage Foundation last fall, all in the same week. Their presentations 
were overshadowed that week by another Heritage speaker: California Gov. Pete 
Wilson, whose denunciation of costly federal mandates made headline news around 
the country and was broadcast repeatedly by SPAN, the Cable-Satellite Public 
Affairs Network.
<p>

<P>
The Heritage Foundation in 1994 remained one of Washington's leading forums. 
Thousands attended the more than 100 public lectures and seminars, and millions 
more watched the proceedings on public-affairs television or read the published 
lectures.
<p>
<B>Among 1994's notable events:</B>
<p>
 The inauguration of a 10-part lecture series, "Sweet Land of Liberty: Strengthening 
America's Culture," sponsored by the Salvatori Foundation. 
<p>
 The Ambassadors Forum on Free Trade, a panel discussion with the four previously 
mentioned ambassadors, held just weeks before the "Summit of the Americas."
<p>
 A major conference on reforming the U.S. agricultural system, featuring three 
former Secretaries of Agriculture: John Block, Earl Butz, and Clayton Yeutter.
<p>
In addition to several governors and numerous members of the House and Senate, 
featured speakers during the year included Heritage Distinguished Fellow <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">William 
Bennett</a>; Mickey Kantor, the U.S. Trade Representative; William Kristol, Chairman 
of the Project for the Republican Future; G. Gordon Liddy, the popular radio 
talk-show host; Gen. Merrill McPeak, the U.S. Air Force Chief of Staff; Gen. 
Gordon Sullivan, the U.S. Army Chief of Staff; Cal Thomas, the popular author, 
columnist, and television talk-show host; and Robert Woodson, President of 
the National Center for Neighborhood Enterprise. 
<p>
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>
</HTML>


