<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Research -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">R</FONT>esearch </I></H2></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>Ammunition For Change</B></CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
"The Heritage Foundation is without question the most far-reaching conservative 
organization in the country in the war of ideas, and one which has had a tremendous 
impact not just in Washington but literally across the planet." - House Speaker 
Newt Gingrich, R-GA.
<p>

<p>

When more than 300 Republican congressional candidates joined House Minority 
Whip Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., on the steps of the Capitol for a Sept. 27 "photo 
op" - intended to focus national attention on the House GOP's "Contract with 
America" - liberal "spin doctors" warned that Gingrich & Company had gravely 
miscalculated.  Weeks later the voters delivered their own verdict: It was 
the spin doctors who had miscalculated.
<P>
The "Contract with America" drew heavily from years of Heritage Foundation 
research.  While not every detail of every proposal was identical to the recommendations 
made over the years by Heritage analysts in their congressional testimony, 
articles, books, and research papers, the similarities were striking.  Said 
the liberal Boston Globe: "As the leading source of scholarship for that [conservative] 
movement, The Heritage Foundation has been able to hammer home a simple message: 
Government programs have done more to worsen the nation's social problems than 
to heal them."          
<P>
Heritage welcomed the 1994 political season with "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/issu.html">Issues '94</a>," a first-of-its-kind 
candidates' briefing book providing comprehensive data on a dozen key national 
issues, from federal spending and defense policy to congressional reform. Newt 
Gingrich, who would become the new Speaker of the House in 1995, called the 
book, which was made available to every House and Senate candidate (and, on 
request, several gubernatorial candidates), an example of Heritage at its best: 
doing "serious work ... and thinking about not just how to get power, but how 
to use power for the nation's good." In the final weeks of the fall campaign, 
talk-radio host Rush Limbaugh read extensive excerpts from "Issues '94," which 
had become a primary reference source for dozens of campaigns. Many of these 
campaigns were successful. 
<P>

<P>

Following the conservative victory in November, Heritage was ready once again 
with a policy blueprint for the new 104th Congress. The 19-chapter "New Member's 
Guide to the Issues" - compared by some to Heritage's Reagan-era "Mandate for 
Leadership" series - offered concrete suggestions for a conservative reordering 
of Washington on issues as diverse as agriculture, the budget, crime, defense 
policy, education, regulation, taxation, and trade. The Guide served as the 
basic "textbook" at Heritage's freshman orientation program for new members 
of Congress, held in December in Baltimore. 
<P>


"Issues '94" and "The New Member's Guide to the Issues" were both collaborative 
efforts involving The Heritage Foundation's entire research staff.



         



</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B33-278</DOCNO>
