<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>untitled.html</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><CENTER><FONT FACE="Palatino" FONT SIZE=+3>1997 George Washington FellowsProgram</FONT></CENTER></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><CENTER><IMG SRC="gwash1.gif" WIDTH="101" HEIGHT="134" ALIGN="LEFT"    NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></CENTER></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE><P><CENTER><HR WIDTH="72%"></CENTER></P><P><CENTER><B><FONT COLOR="#045C1E" SIZE=+2>&quot;Of all the dispositionsand habits which lead to political prosperity, Religion and Morality areindispensable supports.&quot;</FONT></B></CENTER></P><P><CENTER><B><I><FONT COLOR="#045C1E" SIZE=+2>George Washington<BR></FONT></I></B><HR WIDTH="72%"><BR><BR></CENTER></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+1>Discovery Institute is pleased to announce  the 1997 George Washington Fellows Program, an intensive four-week seminar  on religion and politics for upper-level undergraduates, first and second  year graduate students, and recent college graduates seeking careers in  public life. The program is designed to give Fellows an in-depth understanding  of the role religion can play in a free society. The program is limited  to 6-10 Fellows, who will each receive a fellowship in the amount of $1,000.  For a nominal fee, graduate level credit is available for the seminar through  Seattle Pacific University.<BR>  <BR>  Discussions during the program will examine the public role of religion  from the ancient world to the present. Readings may include selections  from the Bible, Hesiod, the Laws of Manu, Thomas Aquinas, Martin Luther,  John Calvin, John Locke, the American Founders, Alexis De Tocqueville,  Harriet Beecher Stowe, Abraham Lincoln, C. S. Lewis, John Courtney Murray,  Martin Luther King, Jr., Harry Jaffa, and others.<BR>  <BR>  In addition to the regular discussion sessions during the program, there  will be special forums on specific issues led by nationally-recognized  scholars and thinkers. Past forums have included &quot;Economics and the  Judeo-Christian Tradition,&quot; with George Gilder, author of <I>Wealth  and Poverty, Men and Marriage</I> and other books; &quot;Church, State,  and the Law,&quot; with former Attorney General Edwin Meese; &quot;Religion  and International Affairs,&quot; with George Weigel, past President of  the Ethics and Public Policy Center; &quot;Academic Freedom and the Refutation  of Scientific Naturalism,&quot; with Stephen Meyer, Director of Discovery  Institute's Center for the Renewal of Science and Culture; &quot;Religion,  Free Speech, and the Equal Access Act,&quot; with Edward Larson, Professor  of History and Law at the University of Georgia; &quot;The Old Testament  and Politics,&quot; led by Rabbi Daniel Lapin, President of Toward Tradition;  and &quot;God and Culture in the Twenty-First Century,&quot; with Phillip  Johnson of the University of California at Berkeley and Father Robert Sirico  of the Acton Institute.<BR>  <BR>  Each Fellow will also be required to write a 10-15 page essay analyzing  some public issue involving the intersection between religion and public  affairs. A draft of the essay is due by June 23. Fellows will discuss and  revise their essays during their time in Seattle.<BR>  </FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><B><FONT COLOR="#99050E" SIZE=+1>Admission Requirements:</FONT></B><FONT     COLOR="#99050E" SIZE=+1> Applicants must be currently enrolled undergraduates    at the junior or senior levels, or graduate students in the first two years    of graduate or law school, or recent college graduates who seek careers    in public life. Required application materials include a copy of the applicant's    academic transcript, two letters of recommendation, a writing sample, and    short statements describing the applicant's career plans and his or her    proposed topic for the essay. <BR>    <BR>    <B>Room, Board, and Travel Costs:</B> In addition to the fellowship of    $1,000, Fellows will be reimbursed up to $400 for travel costs to Seattle.    Fellows will also be provided with lodging, course materials, and some    meals.<BR>    <BR>    <B>Application Deadline:</B> Applications will be accepted until <B><I><TT>April    11, 1997</TT></I></B>, but applications received by March 28 may receive    priority consideration.</FONT></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+1>If you have questions, would like more  information, or would like to receive an applicaiton form please e-mail  Marshall Sana at </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="mailto:msana@discovery.org">msana@discovery.org</A></FONT><FONT   COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+1>.</FONT></B></P>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><CENTER><HR></CENTER></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE><H1><CENTER><A HREF="aboutdis.html"><IMG SRC="aboutdis.gif" WIDTH="107"HEIGHT="46" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="current.html"><IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="106" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><AHREF="front.html"><IMG SRC="image46.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR><A HREF="ggindex.html"><IMG SRC="image47.gif" WIDTH="109" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="crsc.html"><IMG SRC="crscbttn.gif"WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="48" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="whatsnew.html"><IMG SRC="image49.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></CENTER></H1><H3><CENTER><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="147" HEIGHT="59" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></CENTER></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><CENTER><B><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=-1>The George Washington Fellows    Program is sponsored by </FONT><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="index.html">Discovery    Institute</A></FONT><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=-1>, a non-partisan national    public policy center based in Seattle. </FONT