<TITLE>Charles Heatherly</TITLE>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>


<center>

   <hr noshade>

   <A HREF = "../bios.htm">Return to Staff and Fellows</A> ||
   <A HREF = "../index.html">Claremont Institute Home Page</A>

   <hr noshade>

   <H1>Charles Heatherly</H1>

</CENTER>

<p>

	<a href="mailto:cheatherly@msn.com">Charles Heatherly</a> is the Executive Vice President of the Claremont Institute and also serves as Director of the Institute's Golden State Center for Policy Studies in Sacramento.

<p>

	He was born in Tennessee, raised and educated in Arizona, and has worked in Pennsylvania, California, and our nation's capital.

<p>

	He received his B.A. in government and history from the University of Arizona and his M.A. in government from the Claremont Graduate School.  He worked for non-profit educational organizations for fourteen years before turning to government service in the Reagan Administration.  He held three executive positions between 1981 and 1987, including Deputy Under Secretary for Management at the U.S. Dept. of Education and Deputy Administrator of the Small Business Administration. 

<p>

	He knows small business and its problems, and was for six years director of education for the nation's largest small business association, the National Federation of Independent Business.

<p>

	Heatherly has also been active in local government and local schools.  As a resident and public school parent in San Mateo County, California, he volunteered his time as a member of the Burlingame School District Budget Task Force.  He was also on the executive committee of the Governmental Research Council of San Mateo County.  Most recently, he served as Vice Chairman of the Dunfey Group, a statewide coalition of parents and community leaders advocating education reform through radical deregulation, parent empowerment, and independent charter schools.

<p>

	Prior to joining the Claremont Institute in 1993, he was Vice President for Academic Relations at The Heritage Foundation in Washington, D.C.  He edited the now-famous Mandate for Leadership, a blueprint for the Reagan Administration's first 100 days.  He also co-edited that book's sequel, Mandate for Leadership III, written for the Bush Administration.  In 1988 he was project manager for another pioneering Heritage Foundation book, the The Imperial Congress, which included an introduction by a little-known freshman congressman from Georgia, Newt Gingrich.

<p>

	He currently serves as Chairman of the State Policy Network, a federation of thirty state-based research institutes dedicated to free markets, limited government, and individual freedom.

<P>

