<p>

<center>

<h2><font size=+3>P</font>hillip <font size=+3>V</font>. 
<font size=+3>O</font>lsen</h2>

<h3>Vice President for Resource Development</h3>

<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/photos/phil.gif">
<p><hr size=3 width=65%><p>

</center>

Once a gladiator in the trenches of the National Football
League, now a pro-family advocate, Phillip V. Olsen joined the
Family Research Council in 1992 where he is Vice President for
Resource Development.  In his new capacity, the former professional
athlete directs his energies into marketing the pro-family, policy,
lobbying and educational organization.  As FRC takes its analysis
of pro-family policy to our nation's leaders and lawmakers, Mr.
Olsen and his Resource Development team broadcast the news about
FRC to its supporters nationwide.  His work involves the coordination
of resource development and grass roots networking as well as
the oversight of programs, activities and events that deliver
the message of FRC.

<p>

Mr. Olsen may be best known as a consensus first team collegiate
All-American Defensive End who was also a first-round NFL draft
choice in 1970. From there the two year All-American went on to
play nine years in the NFL, until his retirement in 1979.  A highly
decorated athlete during his athletic career, he was inducted
into the State of Utah Sports Hall of Fame in 1985.  He was also
named to Utah State University's All-Century football team in
1993 and was inducted into it's Athletic Hall of Fame in 1994.

<p>

As a concerned professional athlete, Mr. Olsen, and his brothers
Merlin and Orrin, originated and operated the Olsen Brothers All
Sports Camps throughout the western U.S.  He has also initiated
a number of student/athlete enhancement programs to promote athletic
and academic achievement. Mr. Olsen has continued his career
in sports through his work as a color commentator covering college
football on radio and as a member of the NBC TV broadcast support
team covering two Super Bowls and numerous other college and NFL
football games.

<p>

In business, Mr. Olsen has more than twenty years experience
in commercial/industrial real estate.  His experience includes
expertise in real estate finance, development, brokerage and investor
equity funding.

<p>

Active in community service, Mr. Olsen has served as chairman
of the NFL Players Association Men's Committee for Childhelp USA,
a national not-for-profit organization serving abused and battered
children.  He has also been actively involved with a number of
other charities and volunteer organizations such as Life to Life,
Sigma Chi Fraternity, the California Care Coalition, the Billy
Graham Crusade, &quot;Men at the Marriott&quot;, Friends of the
Family Research Council, and South Coast Community Church.

<p>

Mr. Olsen graduated from Utah State University in 1970 with a
Bachelor's degree in business and economics. He and his wife Connie
and their two daughters live in Maryland.

<p><HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 60%><p>

